# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: iucn-red-list
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:iucn-red-list/arkive] The project was an initiative of Wildscreen, a UK-registered educational charity, based in Bristol.
[src:iucn-red-list/arkive] The technical platform was created by Hewlett-Packard, as part of the HP Labs' Digital Media Systems research programme.
[src:iucn-red-list/arkive] It was a member of the Institutional Council of the Encyclopedia of Life.
[src:iucn-red-list/arkive] Two ARKive layers for Google Earth, featuring endangered species and species in the Gulf of Mexico were produced by Google Earth Outreach.
[src:iucn-red-list/arkive] The first of these was launched in April 2008 by Wildscreen's Patron, Sir David Attenborough.
[src:iucn-red-list/arkive] Due to lack of funding, the website was closed on 15 February 2019 and the media collection taken offline.
[src:iucn-red-list/arkive] Its successor, Wildscreen ARK (https://wildscreenark.org/), was launched in February 2024.
[src:iucn-red-list/arkive] The project formally was launched on 20 May 2003 by its patron, the UK-based natural history presenter, Sir David Attenborough, a long-standing colleague and friend of its chief instigator, the late Christopher Parsons, a former Head of the BBC Natural History Unit.
[src:iucn-red-list/arkive] Parsons never lived to see the fruition of the project, succumbing to cancer in November 2002 at the age of 70.
[src:iucn-red-list/arkive] Parsons identified a need to provide a centralised safe haven for wildlife films and photographs after discovering that many such records are held in scattered, non-indexed, collections, often with little or no public access, and sometimes in conditions that could lead to loss or damage.
[src:iucn-red-list/arkive] He believed the records could be a powerful force in building environmental awareness by bringing scientific names to life.
[src:iucn-red-list/arkive] He also saw their preservation as an important educational resource and conservation tool, not at least because extinction rates and habitat destruction could mean that images and sounds might be the only legacy of some species' existence.
[src:iucn-red-list/arkive] Media was digitised to the highest available quality without compression and encoded to open standards.
[src:iucn-red-list/arkive] A prototype site was online as early as April 1999.
[src:iucn-red-list/arkive] There were several design iterations before the formal launch.
[src:iucn-red-list/arkive] By the launch date, the project team had researched, catalogued, copied, described and authenticated image, sound and fact files of 1,000 animals, plants and fungi, many of them critically endangered.
[src:iucn-red-list/arkive] More multi-media profiles are added every month, starting with British flora and fauna and with species included on the Red List – that is, species that are believed to be closest to extinction, according to research by the World Conservation Union.
[src:iucn-red-list/arkive] By January 2006, the database had grown to 2,000 species, 15,000 still images and more than 50 hours of videos.
[src:iucn-red-list/arkive] By 2010, over 5,500 donors had contributed 70,000 film clips and photos of more than 12,000 species.
[src:iucn-red-list/arkive] In February 2019, Wildscreen announced that they "...have had to make the very hard decision to close the Arkive website on 15 February 2019", due to funding issues.
[src:iucn-red-list/arkive] The site was *Sunday Times* website of the year for 2005.
[src:iucn-red-list/arkive] It was a 2010 Webby Award honouree for its outstanding calibre of work, in the 'Education' category, and a 2010 Association of Educational Publishers 'Distinguished Achievement Award' winner, in the category for websites for 9-to-12-year-olds.
[src:iucn-red-list/barcelona-p01] According to tradition, Barcelona was founded by either the Phoenicians or the Carthaginians, who had trading posts along the Catalonian coast.
[src:iucn-red-list/barcelona-p01] In the Middle Ages, Barcelona became the capital of the County of Barcelona.
[src:iucn-red-list/barcelona-p01] Barcelona became the centre of Catalan separatism, briefly becoming part of France during the 17th century Reapers' War and again in 1812 until 1814 under Napoleon.
[src:iucn-red-list/barcelona-p01] After the Spanish transition to democracy in the 1970s, Barcelona once again became the capital of an autonomous Catalonia.
[src:iucn-red-list/barcelona-p01] Barcelona has a rich cultural heritage and is today an important cultural centre and a major tourist destination.
[src:iucn-red-list/barcelona-p01] Particularly renowned are the architectural works of Antoni Gaudí and Lluís Domènech i Montaner, which have been designated UNESCO World Heritage Sites.
[src:iucn-red-list/barcelona-p01] The city is home to two of the most prestigious universities in Spain: the University of Barcelona and Pompeu Fabra University.
[src:iucn-red-list/barcelona-p01] The headquarters of the Union for the Mediterranean are located in Barcelona.
[src:iucn-red-list/barcelona-p01] The city is known for hosting the 1992 Summer Olympics as well as world-class conferences and expositions.
[src:iucn-red-list/barcelona-p01] In addition, many international sport tournaments have been played here.
[src:iucn-red-list/barcelona-p01] Barcelona is a major cultural, economic, and financial centre in southwestern Europe, as well as the main biotech hub in Spain.
[src:iucn-red-list/barcelona-p01] As a leading world city, Barcelona's influence in global socio-economic affairs qualifies it for global city status (Beta +).
[src:iucn-red-list/barcelona-p01] Other sources suggest that the city may have been named after the Carthaginian general Hamilcar Barca, who was supposed to have founded the city in the 3rd century BC, but there is no evidence that its name in antiquity, *Barcino*, was connected with the Barcid family of Hamilcar.
[src:iucn-red-list/barcelona-p01] During the Middle Ages, the city was variously known as *Barchinona*, *Barçalona*, *Barchelonaa*, and *Barchenona*.
[src:iucn-red-list/barcelona-p01] An abbreviated form sometimes used by locals for the city is *Barna*.
[src:iucn-red-list/barcelona-p01] *Barça* is only applied to the local football club FC Barcelona, not to the city.
[src:iucn-red-list/barcelona-p01] Another common abbreviation is 'BCN', which is also the IATA airport code of the Barcelona-El Prat Airport.
[src:iucn-red-list/barcelona-p01] The city is referred to as the *Ciutat Comtal* in Catalan and *Ciudad Condal* in Spanish (i.e., "Comital City" or "City of Counts"), owing to its past as the seat of the Count of Barcelona.
[src:iucn-red-list/barcelona-p01] The origin of the earliest settlement at the site of present-day Barcelona is unclear.
[src:iucn-red-list/barcelona-p01] The ruins of an early settlement have been found, including different tombs and dwellings dating to earlier than 5000 BC.
[src:iucn-red-list/barcelona-p01] In Greek mythology, the founding of Barcelona had been attributed to the mythological Hercules.
[src:iucn-red-list/barcelona-p01] According to tradition, Barcelona was founded by Punic (Phoenician) settlers, who had trading posts along the Catalonian coast.
[src:iucn-red-list/barcelona-p01] In particular, some historians attribute the foundation of the city directly to the historical Carthaginian general, Hamilcar Barca, father of Hannibal, who supposedly named the city *Barcino* after his family in the 3rd century BC, but this theory has been questioned.
[src:iucn-red-list/barcelona-p01] Iberia and Barcelona was controlled by the Carthaginian Empire and was an important location for trade due to its proximity to Punic Ibiza.
[src:iucn-red-list/barcelona-p01] Archeological evidence in the form of coins from the 3rd century BC have been found on the hills at the foot of Montjuïc with the name Bárkeno written in the Iberian script in the Iberian language.
[src:iucn-red-list/barcelona-p01] In about 15 BC, the Romans redrew the town as a *castrum* (Roman military camp) centred on the "*Mons Taber*", a little hill near the Generalitat (Catalan Government) and city hall buildings.
[src:iucn-red-list/barcelona-p01] The Roman Forum, at the crossing of the Cardo Maximus and Decumanus Maximus, was approximately placed where current Plaça de Sant Jaume is.
[src:iucn-red-list/barcelona-p01] Thus, the political centre of the city, Catalonia, and its domains has remained in the same place for over 2,000 years.
[src:iucn-red-list/barcelona-p01] Under the Romans, it was a colony with the surname of *Faventia*, or, in full, *Colonia Faventia Julia Augusta Pia Barcino* or *Colonia Julia Augusta Faventia Paterna Barcino*.
[src:iucn-red-list/barcelona-p01] It enjoyed immunity from imperial burdens.
[src:iucn-red-list/barcelona-p01] The city minted its own coins; some from the era of Galba survive.
[src:iucn-red-list/barcelona-p01] Important Roman vestiges are displayed in Plaça del Rei underground, as a part of the Barcelona City History Museum (MUHBA); the typically Roman grid plan is still visible today in the layout of the historical centre, the *Barri Gòtic* (Gothic Quarter).
[src:iucn-red-list/barcelona-p01] Some remaining fragments of the Roman walls have been incorporated into the cathedral.
[src:iucn-red-list/barcelona-p01] The cathedral, Catedral Basílica Metropolitana de Barcelona, is also sometimes called *La Seu*, which simply means cathedral (and see, among other things) in Catalan.
[src:iucn-red-list/barcelona-p01] The city was conquered by the Visigoths in the early 5th century, becoming for a few years the capital of all Hispania.
[src:iucn-red-list/barcelona-p01] After being conquered by the Umayyads in the early 8th century, it was conquered after a siege in 801 by Charlemagne's son Louis, who made Barcelona the seat of the Carolingian "Hispanic March" (*Marca Hispanica*), a buffer zone ruled by the Count of Barcelona.
[src:iucn-red-list/barcelona-p01] The Counts of Barcelona became increasingly independent and expanded their territory to include much of modern Catalonia, although in 985, Barcelona was sacked by the army of Almanzor.
[src:iucn-red-list/barcelona-p01] The sack was so traumatic that most of Barcelona's population was either killed or enslaved.
[src:iucn-red-list/barcelona-p01] In 1137, Aragon and the County of Barcelona merged in dynastic union by the marriage of Ramon Berenguer IV and Petronilla of Aragon, their titles finally borne by only one person when their son Alfonso II of Aragon ascended to the throne in 1162.
[src:iucn-red-list/barcelona-p01] His territories were later to be known as the Crown of Aragon, which conquered many overseas possessions and ruled the western Mediterranean Sea with outlying territories in Naples and Sicily and as far as Athens in the 13th century.
[src:iucn-red-list/barcelona-p01] Barcelona also had a substantial Jewish community at the time, then the largest Jewish community in the Crown of Aragon.
[src:iucn-red-list/barcelona-p01] Called "the Call," for the many small streets that defined the area, it later became enclosed.
[src:iucn-red-list/barcelona-p01] Montjuïc or Montjuich, in medieval Latin and Catalan, meaning "Jewish Mountain" and the birthplace of the city, is the site of a medieval Jewish cemetery, Jews continued to live in Barcelona until the Massacre of 1391 diminished their numbers.
[src:iucn-red-list/barcelona-p01] The Spanish Inquisition forced the remaining Jews who refused to convert to Christianity to be burned at the stake, or sell their property and leave.
[src:iucn-red-list/barcelona-p01] Barcelona was the leading slave trade centre of the Crown of Aragon up until the 15th century, when it was eclipsed by Valencia.
[src:iucn-red-list/barcelona-p01] It initially fed from eastern and Balkan slave stock later drawing from a Maghribian and, ultimately, Subsaharan pool of slaves.
[src:iucn-red-list/barcelona-p01] The Bank or Taula de canvi de Barcelona, often viewed as the oldest public bank in Europe, was established by the city magistrates in 1401.
[src:iucn-red-list/barcelona-p01] It originated from necessities of the state, as did the Bank of Venice (1402) and the Bank of Genoa (1407).
[src:iucn-red-list/barcelona-p01] In the beginning of the early modern period, Barcelona lost political primacy, but the economy managed to achieve a balance between production capacity and imports.
[src:iucn-red-list/barcelona-p01] In the context of the wider early recovery of Catalonia from the 17th-century crisis in the second half of the century, increasing maritime activity since 1675 doubled traffic in the port of Barcelona compared to figures from the beginning of the 17th century.
[src:iucn-red-list/barcelona-p01] In the late 17th and early 18th century, Barcelona repeatedly endured the effects of war, including the 1691 bombing, the sieges of 1697, 1704, 1705, 1706, and the 1713 blockade and ensuing 1714 siege and assault.
[src:iucn-red-list/barcelona-p01] In the 18th century, the population grew from 30,000 to about 100,000 inhabitants, as the city became one of the key mercantile centres in the Western Mediterranean, with inland influence up to Zaragoza, and to the south up to Alicante.
[src:iucn-red-list/barcelona-p01] A fortress was built at Montjuïc that overlooked the harbour.
[src:iucn-red-list/barcelona-p01] Much of Barcelona was negatively affected by the Napoleonic wars, but the start of industrialization saw the fortunes of the province improve.
[src:iucn-red-list/barcelona-p01] During the 19th century, Catalan business interests, many of them based in Barcelona, became increasingly involved in the Atlantic slave trade, taking advantage of the void left by the British abolition of the trade in 1807.
[src:iucn-red-list/barcelona-p01] Catalan immigrants in Spanish America also became heavily involved in owning and running slave plantations in Cuba and Puerto Rico.
[src:iucn-red-list/barcelona-p01] When slavery was abolished in the Spanish Empire in 1886, many Catalans returned to Barcelona and invested their newfound fortunes in constructing opulent mansions in areas such as La Rambla.
[src:iucn-red-list/barcelona-p01] In the mid-1850s, Barcelona was struggling with population density as it became an industrial, port city and European capital.
[src:iucn-red-list/barcelona-p01] The city's density was at 856 people per hectare, more than double that of Paris.
[src:iucn-red-list/barcelona-p01] Mortality rates were on the rise and any outbreaks of disease would devastate the population.
[src:iucn-red-list/barcelona-p01] To solve the issue, a civil engineer named Ildefons Cerdà proposed a plan for a new district known as the Eixample.
[src:iucn-red-list/barcelona-p01] The citizens of Barcelona had begun to demolish the medieval wall surrounding and constricting the city.
[src:iucn-red-list/barcelona-p01] Cerdà thought it best to transform the land outside the walls into an area characterized by a scientific approach to urbanization.
[src:iucn-red-list/barcelona-p01] His proposal consisted of a grid of streets to unite the old city and surrounding villages.
[src:iucn-red-list/barcelona-p01] There would also be wide streets to allow people to breathe clean air, gardens in the centre of each street block, integration of rich and poor giving both groups access to the same services, and smooth-flowing traffic.
[src:iucn-red-list/barcelona-p01] Urban quality, egalitarianism, hygiene, sunlight, and efficiency were all major keys for Cerdà's vision.
[src:iucn-red-list/barcelona-p01] Not everything he imagined would be realized within the Eixample district, but the iconic octagonal superblocks with chamfered corners for better visibility are his direct brainchild and remain immensely helpful even 170 years later.
[src:iucn-red-list/barcelona-p01] The district and its ideals were not appreciated at the time.
[src:iucn-red-list/barcelona-p01] The city council awarded the design of the extension plan to another architect.
[src:iucn-red-list/barcelona-p01] The Spanish government was the one to step in and impose Cerdà's plan, laying the groundwork for many more tensions between the Spanish and Catalan administrations.
[src:iucn-red-list/barcelona-p01] Regardless, some of the upper class citizens of Barcelona were excited by the new plan and began a race to build "the biggest, tallest, most attractive house" in the district.
[src:iucn-red-list/barcelona-p01] Their interest and money fueled the rich diversity that we now see in the district's architecture.
[src:iucn-red-list/barcelona-p01] In the end, Cerdà's ideas would have a lasting impact on Barcelona's development, earning it international recognition for its highly efficient approach to urban planning and design.
[src:iucn-red-list/barcelona-p01] Shortly after the establishment of the Second Spanish Republic, in 1931, it became the capital of the autonomous region of Catalonia.
[src:iucn-red-list/barcelona-p01] During the Spanish Civil War, the city, and Catalonia in general, were resolutely Republican.
[src:iucn-red-list/barcelona-p01] Many enterprises and public services were collectivized by the CNT and UGT unions.
[src:iucn-red-list/barcelona-p01] As the power of the Republican government and the Generalitat diminished, much of the city was under the effective control of anarchist groups.
[src:iucn-red-list/barcelona-p01] The anarchists lost control of the city to their own allies, the Communists and official government troops, after the street fighting of the Barcelona May Days.
[src:iucn-red-list/barcelona-p01] Barcelona was one of the last places in Spain to fall under Francoist control, and became the capital of the Second Spanish Republic in November 1937.
[src:iucn-red-list/barcelona-p01] From 16 to 18 March 1938, Barcelona was bombed several times by Fascist Italy and Nazi Germany, in support of the Francoist-led army.
[src:iucn-red-list/barcelona-p01] It left at least 1,300 people killed and 2,000 wounded.
[src:iucn-red-list/barcelona-p01] The airstrikes intended to destroy industrial areas and demoralize the republicans, however civil buildings were also destroyed.
[src:iucn-red-list/barcelona-p01] The fall of the city on 26 January 1939, caused a mass exodus of civilians who fled to the French border.
[src:iucn-red-list/barcelona-p01] The resistance of Barcelona to Franco's *coup d'état* was to have lasting effects after the defeat of the Republican government.
[src:iucn-red-list/barcelona-p01] The autonomous institutions of Catalonia were abolished, and the use of the Catalan language in public life was suppressed.
[src:iucn-red-list/barcelona-p01] Barcelona remained the second largest city in Spain, at the heart of a region which was relatively industrialized and prosperous, despite the devastation of the civil war.
[src:iucn-red-list/barcelona-p01] The result was a large-scale immigration from poorer regions of Spain (particularly Andalusia, Murcia and Galicia), which in turn led to rapid urbanization.
[src:iucn-red-list/barcelona-p01] During the francoist period, municipal elections were suspended through all Spain and the mayor was appointed by the central government.
[src:iucn-red-list/barcelona-p01] Pressure for change was particularly strong in Barcelona, which considered that it had been punished during nearly forty years of Francoism for its support of the Republican government.
[src:iucn-red-list/barcelona-p01] After Franco's death in 1975, massive peaceful demonstrations on 11 September 1977 assembled over a million people in the streets of Barcelona to call for the restoration of Catalan autonomy.
[src:iucn-red-list/barcelona-p01] After the adoption of the Constitution, municipal elections were held again (1979).
[src:iucn-red-list/barcelona-p01] The development of Barcelona was promoted by two events in 1986: Spanish accession to the European Community, and particularly Barcelona's designation as host city of the 1992 Summer Olympics.
[src:iucn-red-list/barcelona-p01] The process of urban regeneration has been rapid, and accompanied by a greatly increased international reputation of the city as a tourist destination.
[src:iucn-red-list/barcelona-p01] The increased cost of housing has led to a slight decline (−16.6%) in the population over the last two decades of the 20th century as many families move out into the suburbs.
[src:iucn-red-list/barcelona-p01] This decline has been reversed since 2001, as a new wave of immigration (particularly from Latin America and from Morocco) has gathered pace.
[src:iucn-red-list/barcelona-p01] In 1987, an ETA car bombing at Hipercor killed 21 people.
[src:iucn-red-list/barcelona-p01] In 1992, Barcelona hosted the Summer Olympics.
[src:iucn-red-list/barcelona-p01] The after-effects of this are credited with driving major changes in what had, up until then, been a largely industrial city.
[src:iucn-red-list/barcelona-p01] As part of the preparation for the games, industrial buildings along the sea-front were demolished and 3 km (2 mi) of beach were created.
[src:iucn-red-list/barcelona-p01] New construction increased the road capacity of the city by 17%, the sewage handling capacity by 27% and the amount of new green areas and beaches by 78%.
[src:iucn-red-list/barcelona-p01] Between 1990 and 2004, the number of hotel rooms in the city doubled.
[src:iucn-red-list/barcelona-p01] Perhaps more importantly, the outside perception of the city was changed making, by 2012, Barcelona the 12th most popular city destination in the world and the 5th amongst European cities.
[src:iucn-red-list/barcelona-p01] The year 2017 was an intense year in Barcelona.
[src:iucn-red-list/barcelona-p01] On August 17, Barcelona suffered a terrorist attack in the iconic Rambla, where a van drove into pedestrians, killing 13 people and injuring at least 130 others.
[src:iucn-red-list/barcelona-p01] The perpetrator fled on foot, killing another person to steal his car, and a large police operation was started.
[src:iucn-red-list/barcelona-p01] Massive demonstrations in the city center took place the days after the attack, with the motto "*No tinc por*" ("I am not afraid").
[src:iucn-red-list/barcelona-p01] Other attacks took place elsewhere in Catalonia.
[src:iucn-red-list/barcelona-p01] The Prime Minister of Spain, Mariano Rajoy, called the attack in Barcelona a jihadist attack.
[src:iucn-red-list/barcelona-p01] Amaq News Agency attributed indirect responsibility for the attack to the Islamic State of Iraq and the Levant (ISIL).
[src:iucn-red-list/barcelona-p01] On October 2017, after several years of growing of the Catalan independence movement, with massive demonstrations along the decade, an independence referendum took place.
[src:iucn-red-list/barcelona-p01] It was declared unconstitutional by the Spanish Constitutional Court, however the Catalan Government ignored it and celebrated it.
[src:iucn-red-list/barcelona-p01] This led to another court ordering the Spanish Civil Guard and National Police to dismantle voting centers, however their intervention was not pacific.
[src:iucn-red-list/barcelona-p01] Barcelona was the scenario of several police oppression and chaos, with sources that reported at least 1,066 injured requiring medical attention.
[src:iucn-red-list/barcelona-p01] Several NGOs condemned the police's violence and reported an excessive use of force.
[src:iucn-red-list/barcelona-p01] The referendum sparked the 2017–2018 Spanish constitutional crisis, and later protests took place.
[src:iucn-red-list/barcelona-p01] In July 2023, Barcelona was announced as the UNESCO-UIA World Capital of Architecture for the 2024–2026 term.
[src:iucn-red-list/barcelona-p01] This means it will be the hub for discussion around global challenges including culture, heritage, urban planning and architecture.
[src:iucn-red-list/barcelona-p01] In addition to being the capital through 2026, it will also host the UIA World Congress of Architects for that year.
[src:iucn-red-list/barcelona-p01] The honour is befitting of Barcelona, as its history is peppered with architectural achievement and various iconic styles and influences.
[src:iucn-red-list/barcelona-p01] From its ancient Roman roots, to the Gothic and Modernisme movements, Barcelona has thrived through the way it ties together architecture and culture.
[src:iucn-red-list/barcelona-p01] Barcelona is located on the northeast coast of the Iberian Peninsula, facing the Mediterranean Sea, on a plain approximately 5 km (3 mi) wide limited by the mountain range of Collserola, the Llobregat river to the southwest and the Besòs river to the north.
[src:iucn-red-list/barcelona-p01] This plain covers an area of 170 km2 (66 sq mi), of which 101 km2 (39.0 sq mi) are occupied by the city itself.
[src:iucn-red-list/barcelona-p01] It is 120 km (75 mi) south of the Pyrenees and the Catalan border with France.
[src:iucn-red-list/barcelona-p01] Tibidabo, 512 m (1,680 ft) high, offers striking views over the city and is topped by the 288.4 m (946.2 ft) Torre de Collserola, a telecommunications tower that is visible from most of the city.
[src:iucn-red-list/barcelona-p01] Barcelona is peppered with small hills, most of them urbanized, that gave their name to the neighbourhoods built upon them, such as Carmel (267 m or 876 ft), Putxet (es) (181 m or 594 ft) and Rovira (261 m or 856 ft).
[src:iucn-red-list/barcelona-p01] The escarpment of Montjuïc (173 m or 568 ft), situated to the southeast, overlooks the harbour and is topped by Montjuïc Castle, a fortress built in the 17–18th centuries to control the city as a replacement for the Ciutadella.
[src:iucn-red-list/barcelona-p01] Today, the fortress is a museum and Montjuïc is home to several sporting and cultural venues, as well as Barcelona's biggest park and gardens.
[src:iucn-red-list/barcelona-p01] The municipality includes two small sparsely-inhabited exclaves to the north-west.
[src:iucn-red-list/barcelona-p01] According to the Köppen climate classification, Barcelona has a hot summer Mediterranean climate (*Csa*), with mild winters and warm to hot summers, while the rainiest seasons are autumn and spring.
[src:iucn-red-list/barcelona-p01] The rainfall pattern is characterized by a short (3 months) dry season in summer, as well as less winter rainfall than in a typical Mediterranean climate.
[src:iucn-red-list/barcelona-p01] However, both June and August are wetter than February, which is unusual for the Mediterranean climate.
[src:iucn-red-list/barcelona-p01] This subtype, labelled as "Portuguese" by the French geographer George Viers after the climate classification of Emmanuel de Martonne and found in the NW Mediterranean area (e.g.
[src:iucn-red-list/barcelona-p01] Marseille), can be seen as transitional to the humid subtropical climate (*Cfa*) found in inland areas.
[src:iucn-red-list/barcelona-p01] Barcelona is densely populated, thus heavily influenced by the urban heat island effect.
[src:iucn-red-list/barcelona-p01] Areas outside of the urbanized districts can have as much as 2 °C of difference in temperatures throughout the year.
[src:iucn-red-list/barcelona-p01] Its average annual temperature is 21.2 °C (70.2 °F) during the day and 15.1 °C (59.2 °F) at night.
[src:iucn-red-list/barcelona-p01] The average annual temperature of the sea is about 20 °C (68 °F).
[src:iucn-red-list/barcelona-p01] In the coldest month, January, the temperature typically ranges from 12 to 18 °C (54 to 64 °F) during the day, 6 to 12 °C (43 to 54 °F) at night and the average sea temperature is 13 °C (55 °F).
[src:iucn-red-list/barcelona-p01] In the warmest month, August, the typical temperature ranges from 27 to 31 °C (81 to 88 °F) during the day, about 23 °C (73 °F) at night and the average sea temperature is 26 °C (79 °F).
[src:iucn-red-list/barcelona-p01] Generally, the summer or "holiday" season lasts about six months, from May to October.
[src:iucn-red-list/barcelona-p01] Two months – April and November – are transitional; sometimes the temperature exceeds 20 °C (68 °F), with an average temperature of 18–19 °C (64–66 °F) during the day and 11–13 °C (52–55 °F) at night.
[src:iucn-red-list/barcelona-p01] December, January and February are the coldest months, with average temperatures around 15 °C (59 °F) during the day and 9 °C (48 °F) at night.
[src:iucn-red-list/barcelona-p01] Large fluctuations in temperature are rare, particularly in the summer months.
[src:iucn-red-list/barcelona-p01] Because of the proximity to the warm sea plus the urban heat island, frosts are very rare in the city of Barcelona.
[src:iucn-red-list/barcelona-p01] Snow is also very infrequent in the city of Barcelona, but light snowfalls can occur yearly in the nearby Collserola mountains, such as in the Fabra Observatory located in a nearby mountain.
[src:iucn-red-list/barcelona-p01] Barcelona averages 78 rainy days per year (≥ 1 mm), and annual average relative humidity is 72%, ranging from 69% in July to 75% in October.
[src:iucn-red-list/barcelona-p01] Rainfall totals are highest in late summer and autumn (September–November) and lowest in early and mid-summer (June–August), with a secondary winter minimum (February–March).
[src:iucn-red-list/barcelona-p01] Sunshine duration is 2,524 hours per year, from 138 (average 4.5 hours of sunshine a day) in December to 310 (average 10 hours of sunshine a day) in July.
[src:iucn-red-list/barcelona-p01] It is the main component of an administrative area of Greater Barcelona, with a population of 3,218,071 in an area of 636 km2 (246 sq mi) (density 5,060 inhabitants/km2).
[src:iucn-red-list/barcelona-p01] The population of the urban area was 4,840,000.
[src:iucn-red-list/barcelona-p01] It is the central nucleus of the Barcelona metropolitan area, which relies on a population of 5,474,482.
[src:iucn-red-list/barcelona-p01] In 1900, Barcelona had a population of 533,000, which grew steadily but slowly until 1950, when it started absorbing a high number of people from other less-industrialized parts of Spain.
[src:iucn-red-list/barcelona-p01] Barcelona's population peaked in 1979 at 1,906,998, and fell throughout the 1980s and 1990s as more people sought a higher quality of life in outlying cities in the Barcelona Metropolitan Area.
[src:iucn-red-list/barcelona-p01] After bottoming out in 2000 with 1,496,266 residents, the city's population began to rise again as younger people started to return, causing a great increase in housing prices.
[src:iucn-red-list/barcelona-p01] Catalan is the "own language" of Catalonia and Barcelona, and therefore its the main language used by the City Council, in schools and it dominates the linguistic landscape.
[src:iucn-red-list/barcelona-p01] All toponymy of Barcelona, including the stops of the metro system, are exclusively in the Catalan language.
[src:iucn-red-list/barcelona-p01] Despite this, Spanish is the most spoken language in Barcelona (according to the linguistic census held by the Government of Catalonia in 2013) and it is understood almost universally.
[src:iucn-red-list/barcelona-p01] Catalan is also very commonly spoken in the city: it is understood by 95% of the population, while 72.3% can speak it, 79% can read it, and 53% can write it.
[src:iucn-red-list/barcelona-p01] Knowledge of Catalan has increased significantly in recent decades thanks to a language immersion educational system.
[src:iucn-red-list/barcelona-p01] After Catalan and Spanish, the most spoken languages in Barcelona are those from North Africa, such as Amazigh and Arabic, followed by Bengali, Urdu, Punjabi, Mandarin Chinese, Romanian, English, Russian and Quechua, according to data collected by the University of Barcelona.
[src:iucn-red-list/barcelona-p01] Barcelona is one of the most densely populated cities in Europe.
[src:iucn-red-list/barcelona-p01] In 2008, the city council calculated the population to 1,621,090 living in the 102.2 km2 sized municipality, giving the city an average population density of 15,926 inhabitants per square kilometre with Eixample being the most populated district.
[src:iucn-red-list/barcelona-p01] In the case of Barcelona though, the land distribution is extremely uneven.
[src:iucn-red-list/barcelona-p01] Half of the municipality or 50.2 km2, all of it located on the municipal edge is made up of the ten least densely populated neighbourhoods containing less than 10% of the city's population, the uninhabited Zona Franca industrial area and Montjuïc forest park.
[src:iucn-red-list/barcelona-p01] Leaving the remaining 90% or slightly below 1.5 million inhabitants living on the remaining 52 km2 (20 sq mi) at an average density close to 28,500 inhabitants per square kilometre.
[src:iucn-red-list/barcelona-p01] Of the 73 neighbourhoods in the city, 45 had a population density above 20,000 inhabitants per square kilometre with a combined population of 1,313,424 inhabitants living on 38.6 km2 at an average density of 33,987 inhabitants per square kilometre.
[src:iucn-red-list/barcelona-p01] The 30 most densely populated neighbourhoods accounted for 57.5% of the city population occupying only 22.7% of the municipality, or in other words, 936,406 people living at an average density of 40,322 inhabitants per square kilometre.
[src:iucn-red-list/barcelona-p01] The city's highest density is found at and around the neighbourhood of la Sagrada Família where four of the city's most densely populated neighbourhoods are located side by side, all with a population density above 50,000 inhabitants per square kilometre.
[src:iucn-red-list/barcelona-p01] In 1900, almost a third (28.9 percent) of the population were children (aged younger than 14 years).
[src:iucn-red-list/barcelona-p01] In 2017, this age group constituted only 12.7% of the population.
[src:iucn-red-list/barcelona-p01] In 2017, people aged between 15 and 24 years made up 9 percent of the population; those aged between 25 and 44 years made up 30.6 percent of the population; while those aged between 45 and 64 years formed 56.9% of all Barcelonans.
[src:iucn-red-list/barcelona-p01] In 1900, people aged 65 and older made up just 6.5 percent of the population.
[src:iucn-red-list/barcelona-p01] In 2017, this age group made up 21.5 percent of the population.
[src:iucn-red-list/barcelona-p01] In 2016, about 59% of the inhabitants of the city were born in Catalonia and 18.5% coming from the rest of the country.
[src:iucn-red-list/barcelona-p01] In addition to that, 22.5% of the population was born outside of Spain, a proportion which has more than doubled since 2001 and more than quintupled since 1996 when it was 8.6% and 3.9% respectively.
[src:iucn-red-list/barcelona-p01] The most important region of origin of migrants is Europe, with many coming from Italy (26,676) or France (13,506).
[src:iucn-red-list/barcelona-p01] Moreover, many migrants come from Latin American nations such as Bolivia, Ecuador or Colombia.
[src:iucn-red-list/barcelona-p01] Since the 1990s, and similar to other migrants, many Latin Americans have settled in northern parts of the city.
[src:iucn-red-list/barcelona-p01] There exists a relatively large Pakistani community in Barcelona with up to twenty thousand nationals.
[src:iucn-red-list/barcelona-p01] The community consists of significantly more men than women.
[src:iucn-red-list/barcelona-p01] Many of the Pakistanis are living in Ciutat Vella.
[src:iucn-red-list/barcelona-p01] First Pakistani migrants came in the 1970s, with increasing numbers in the 1990s.
[src:iucn-red-list/barcelona-p01] Other significant migrant groups come from Asia as from China and the Philippines.
[src:iucn-red-list/barcelona-p01] There is a Japanese community clustered in Bonanova, Les Tres Torres, Pedralbes, and other northern neighbourhoods, and a Japanese international school serves that community.
[src:iucn-red-list/barcelona-p01] In 2007, most of the inhabitants stated they are Roman Catholic (208 churches).
[src:iucn-red-list/barcelona-p01] In a 2011 survey conducted by InfoCatólica, 49.5% of Barcelona residents of all ages identified themselves as Catholic.
[src:iucn-red-list/barcelona-p01] This was the first time that more than half of respondents did not identify themselves as Catholic Christians.
[src:iucn-red-list/barcelona-p01] The numbers reflect a broader trend in Spain whereby the numbers of self-identified Catholics have declined.
[src:iucn-red-list/barcelona-p01] In 2019, a survey by Centro de Investigaciones Sociológicas showed that 53.2% of residents in Barcelona identified themselves as Catholic (9.9% practising Catholics, 43.3% non-practising Catholics).
[src:iucn-red-list/barcelona-p01] The province has the largest Muslim community in Spain, 322,698 people in Barcelona province are of Muslim religion.
[src:iucn-red-list/barcelona-p01] A considerable number of Muslims live in Barcelona due to immigration (169 locations, mostly professed by Moroccans in Spain).
[src:iucn-red-list/barcelona-p01] In 2014, 322,698 out of 5.5 million people in the province of Barcelona identified themselves as Muslim, which makes 5.6% of the total population.
[src:iucn-red-list/barcelona-p01] The city also has the largest Jewish community in Spain, with an estimated 3,500 Jews living in the city.
[src:iucn-red-list/barcelona-p01] There are also a number of other groups, including Evangelical (71 locations, mostly professed by Roma), Jehovah's Witnesses (21 Kingdom Halls), Buddhists (13 locations), and Eastern Orthodox.
[src:iucn-red-list/barcelona-p01] The Barcelona metropolitan area comprises over 66% of the people of Catalonia, one of the richer regions in Europe and the fourth richest region per capita in Spain, with a GDP per capita amounting to €28,400 (16% more than the EU average).
[src:iucn-red-list/barcelona-p01] The greater Barcelona metropolitan area had a GDP amounting to $177 billion (equivalent to $34,821 in per capita terms, 44% more than the EU average), making it the 4th most economically powerful city by gross GDP in the European Union, and 35th in the world in 2009.
[src:iucn-red-list/barcelona-p01] Barcelona city had a very high GDP of €80,894 per head in 2004, according to Eurostat.
[src:iucn-red-list/barcelona-p01] Furthermore, Barcelona was Europe's fourth best business city and fastest improving European city, with growth improved by 17% per year as of 2009.
[src:iucn-red-list/barcelona-p01] Barcelona was the 24th most "livable city" in the world in 2015 according to lifestyle magazine *Monocle*.
[src:iucn-red-list/barcelona-p01] Similarly, according to Innovation Analysts 2thinknow, Barcelona occupies 13th place in the world on *Innovation Cities™ Global Index*.
[src:iucn-red-list/barcelona-p01] At the same time it is according to the Global Wealth and Lifestyle Report 2020 one of the most affordable cities in the world for a luxury lifestyle.
[src:iucn-red-list/barcelona-p01] Barcelona has a long-standing mercantile tradition.
[src:iucn-red-list/barcelona-p01] Less well known is that the city industrialized early, taking off in 1833, when Catalonia's already sophisticated textile industry began to use steam power.
[src:iucn-red-list/barcelona-p01] It became the first and most important industrial city in the Mediterranean basin.
[src:iucn-red-list/barcelona-p01] Since then, manufacturing has played a large role in its history.
[src:iucn-red-list/barcelona-p01] Borsa de Barcelona (Barcelona Stock Exchange) is the main stock exchange in the northeastern part of the Iberian Peninsula.
[src:iucn-red-list/barcelona-p01] Barcelona was recognized as the Southern European City of the Future for 2014/15, based on its economic potential, by *FDi Magazine* in their bi-annual rankings.
[src:iucn-red-list/barcelona-p01] It also has several congress halls, notably Fira de Barcelona – the second largest trade fair and exhibition centre in Europe, that host a quickly growing number of national and international events each year (at present above 50).
[src:iucn-red-list/barcelona-p01] The total exhibition floor space of Fira de Barcelona venues is 405,000 m2 (41 ha), not counting Gran Via centre on the Plaza de Europa.
[src:iucn-red-list/barcelona-p01] However, the Eurozone crisis and deep cuts in business travel affected the council's positioning of the city as a convention centre.
[src:iucn-red-list/barcelona-p01] An important business centre, the World Trade Center Barcelona, is located in Barcelona's Port Vell harbour.
[src:iucn-red-list/barcelona-p01] The city is known for hosting well as world-class conferences and expositions, including the 1888 *Exposición Universal de Barcelona*, the 1929 Barcelona International Exposition (Expo 1929), the 2004 Universal Forum of Cultures and the 2004 World Urban Forum.
[src:iucn-red-list/barcelona-p01] In 2023, Barcelona was the 9th most visited city in the world by international visitors and the fifth most visited city in Europe after Paris, Madrid, Amsterdam, and Rome, with around 9 million international arrivals.
[src:iucn-red-list/barcelona-p01] Due to its large influx of tourists each year, Barcelona, like many other tourism capitals, has to deal with pickpockets, with wallets and passports being commonly stolen items.
[src:iucn-red-list/barcelona-p01] While tourism produces economic benefits, according to one report, the city is "overrun [by] hordes of tourists".
[src:iucn-red-list/barcelona-p01] In early 2017, over 150,000 protesters warned that tourism is destabilizing the city.
[src:iucn-red-list/barcelona-p01] Slogans included "Tourists go home", "Barcelona is not for sale" and "We will not be driven out".
[src:iucn-red-list/barcelona-p01] By then, the number of visitors had increased from 1.7 million in 1990 to 32 million in a city with a population of 1.62 million, increasing the cost of rental housing for residents and overcrowding the public places.
[src:iucn-red-list/barcelona-p01] While tourists spent an estimated €30 billion in 2017, they are viewed by some as a threat to Barcelona's identity.
[src:iucn-red-list/barcelona-p01] A May 2017 article in the British online daily *The Independent* included Barcelona among the "Eight Places That Hate Tourists the Most" and included a comment from Mayor Ada Colau, "We don't want the city to become a cheap souvenir shop", citing Venice as an example.
[src:iucn-red-list/barcelona-p01] To moderate the problem, the city has stopped issuing licenses for new hotels and holiday apartments; it also fined AirBnb €30,000.
[src:iucn-red-list/barcelona-p01] The mayor has suggested introducing a new tourist tax and setting a limit on the number of visitors.
[src:iucn-red-list/barcelona-p01] One industry insider, Justin Francis, founder of the Responsible Travel agency, stated that steps must be taken to limit the number of visitors that are causing an "overtourism crisis" in several major European cities.
[src:iucn-red-list/barcelona-p01] "Ultimately, residents must be prioritised over tourists for housing, infrastructure and access to services because they have a long-term stake in the city's success", he said.
[src:iucn-red-list/barcelona-p01] "Managing tourism more responsibly can help", Francis later told a journalist, "but some destinations may just have too many tourists, and Barcelona may be a case of that".
[src:iucn-red-list/barcelona-p01] In April 2024 protests against overtourism began in the city, reaching its peak in July 2024.
[src:iucn-red-list/barcelona-p01] These protests caught further attention again in July 2025, as similar protests took place in Southern Europe and included Palma, and Lisbon, organized by the Southern Europe Network Against Touristification (SET).
[src:iucn-red-list/barcelona-p01] During the protests some protesters used large water guns to spray water on tourists.
[src:iucn-red-list/barcelona-p01] Industry generates 21% of the total gross domestic product (GDP) of the region, with the energy, chemical and metallurgy industries accounting for 47% of industrial production.
[src:iucn-red-list/barcelona-p01] The Barcelona metropolitan area had 67% of the total number of industrial establishments in Catalonia as of 1997.
[src:iucn-red-list/barcelona-p01] Barcelona has long been an important European automobile manufacturing centre.
[src:iucn-red-list/barcelona-p01] Formerly there were automobile factories of AFA, Abadal, Actividades Industriales, Alvarez, America, Artés de Arcos, Balandrás, Baradat-Esteve, Biscúter, J.
[src:iucn-red-list/barcelona-p01] Today, the headquarters and a large factory of SEAT (the largest Spanish automobile manufacturer) are in one of its suburbs.
[src:iucn-red-list/barcelona-p01] There is also a Nissan factory in the logistics and industrial area of the city.
[src:iucn-red-list/barcelona-p01] The factory of Derbi, a large manufacturer of motorcycles, scooters and mopeds, also lies near the city.
[src:iucn-red-list/barcelona-p01] As in other modern cities, the manufacturing sector has long since been overtaken by the services sector, though it remains very important.
[src:iucn-red-list/barcelona-p01] The region's leading industries are textiles, chemical, pharmaceutical, motor, electronic, printing, logistics, publishing, in telecommunications industry and culture the notable Mobile World Congress, and information technology services.
[src:iucn-red-list/barcelona-p01] The traditional importance of textiles is reflected in Barcelona's drive to become a major fashion centre.
[src:iucn-red-list/barcelona-p01] There have been many attempts to launch Barcelona as a fashion capital, notably *Gaudi Home*.
[src:iucn-red-list/barcelona-p01] Beginning in the summer of 2000, the city hosted the Bread & Butter urban fashion fair until 2009, when its organizers announced that it would be returning to Berlin.
[src:iucn-red-list/barcelona-p01] This was a hard blow for the city as the fair brought €100 m to the city in just three days.
[src:iucn-red-list/barcelona-p01] From 2009, *The Brandery*, an urban fashion show, was held in Barcelona twice a year until 2012.
[src:iucn-red-list/barcelona-p01] According to the Global Language Monitor's annual ranking of the world's top fifty fashion capitals Barcelona was named as the seventh most important fashion capital of the world right after Milan and before Berlin in 2015.
[src:iucn-red-list/barcelona-p01] Several technology companies have offices in Barcelona, most of them in the El Poblenou neighborhood.
[src:iucn-red-list/barcelona-p01] Examples of technology companies based in Barcelona: Factorial (software company), Glovo, TravelPerk, Wallapop, EDreams.
[src:iucn-red-list/barcelona-p01] Technology companies not based in Barcelona but having an office in the city include Oracle Corporation, Amazon (company), King (company), Dynatrace, Clarivate, Ocado, Sage Group, Smallpdf, Proton Mail, Hewlett-Packard, Personio, Semrush.
[src:iucn-red-list/barcelona-p01] Barcelona was ranked as the number 1 startup hub in Southern Europe, and as the 33rd best city in the Global Started Ecosystem published by Startupblink.
[src:iucn-red-list/barcelona-p01] The Barcelona Supercomputing Center is located in Barcelona and hosts the MareNostrum supercomputer.
[src:iucn-red-list/barcelona-p02] As the capital of the autonomous community of Catalonia, Barcelona is the seat of the Catalan government, known as the *Generalitat de Catalunya*; of particular note are the executive branch, the parliament, and the High Court of Justice of Catalonia.
[src:iucn-red-list/barcelona-p02] The city is also the capital of the Province of Barcelona and the Barcelonès comarca (district).
[src:iucn-red-list/barcelona-p02] Barcelona is governed by a city council formed by 41 city councillors, elected for a four-year term by universal suffrage.
[src:iucn-red-list/barcelona-p02] As one of the two biggest cities in Spain, Barcelona is subject to a special law articulated through the *Carta Municipal* (Municipal Law).
[src:iucn-red-list/barcelona-p02] A first version of this law was passed in 1960 and amended later, but the current version was approved in March 2006.
[src:iucn-red-list/barcelona-p02] According to this law, Barcelona's city council is organized in two levels: a political one, with elected city councillors, and one executive, which administers the programs and executes the decisions taken on the political level.
[src:iucn-red-list/barcelona-p02] This law also gives the local government a special relationship with the central government and it also gives the mayor wider prerogatives by the means of municipal executive commissions.
[src:iucn-red-list/barcelona-p02] It expands the powers of the city council in areas like telecommunications, city traffic, road safety and public safety.
[src:iucn-red-list/barcelona-p02] It also gives a special economic regime to the city's treasury and it gives the council a veto in matters that will be decided by the central government, but that will need a favourable report from the council.
[src:iucn-red-list/barcelona-p02] The *Comissió de Govern* (Government Commission) is the executive branch, formed by 24 councillors, led by the Mayor, with 5 lieutenant-mayors and 17 city councillors, each in charge of an area of government, and 5 non-elected councillors.
[src:iucn-red-list/barcelona-p02] The plenary, formed by the 41 city councillors, has advisory, planning, regulatory, and fiscal executive functions.
[src:iucn-red-list/barcelona-p02] The six *Commissions del Consell Municipal* (City council commissions) have executive and controlling functions in the field of their jurisdiction.
[src:iucn-red-list/barcelona-p02] They are composed by a number of councillors proportional to the number of councillors each political party has in the plenary.
[src:iucn-red-list/barcelona-p02] Some of these competencies are not exclusive, but shared with the Generalitat de Catalunya or the central Spanish government.
[src:iucn-red-list/barcelona-p02] In some fields with shared responsibility (such as public health, education or social services), there is a shared Agency or Consortium between the city and the Generalitat to plan and manage services.
[src:iucn-red-list/barcelona-p02] The executive branch is led by a Chief Municipal Executive Officer which answers to the Mayor.
[src:iucn-red-list/barcelona-p02] It is made up of departments which are legally part of the city council and by separate legal entities of two types: autonomous public departments and public enterprises.
[src:iucn-red-list/barcelona-p02] The seat of the city council is on the Plaça de Sant Jaume, opposite the seat of Generalitat de Catalunya.
[src:iucn-red-list/barcelona-p02] Since the coming of the Spanish democracy, Barcelona had been governed by the PSC, first with an absolute majority and later in coalition with ERC and ICV.
[src:iucn-red-list/barcelona-p02] After the May 2007 election, the ERC did not renew the coalition agreement and the PSC governed in a minority coalition with ICV as the junior partner.
[src:iucn-red-list/barcelona-p02] After 32 years, on 22 May 2011, CiU gained a plurality of seats at the municipal election, gaining 15 seats to the PSC's 11.
[src:iucn-red-list/barcelona-p02] Public safety in Barcelona is the duty of the City Council and the Government of Catalonia, who provide it through 2 police forces: the *Guàrdia Urbana de Barcelona* and the *Mossos d'Esquadra*, respectively.
[src:iucn-red-list/barcelona-p02] Before 2008, public safety was also conducted by the National Police Corps, however their duties are now delegated to documental and immigration purposes.
[src:iucn-red-list/barcelona-p02] Medical emergencies are attended by the System of Medical Emergencies, while fire and rescue emergencies are attended by the *Bombers de Barcelona*.
[src:iucn-red-list/barcelona-p02] Maritime rescue is provided by the Maritime Safety and Rescue Society, the Civil Guard and *Mossos* (with the support of *Guàrdia Urbana* during the summer).
[src:iucn-red-list/barcelona-p02] The protection of the wildlife of the part of Collserola Park inside municipal limits is the duty of the Rural Agents Corps.
[src:iucn-red-list/barcelona-p02] The districts are based mostly on historical divisions, and several are former towns annexed by the city of Barcelona in the 18th and 19th centuries that still maintain their own distinct character.
[src:iucn-red-list/barcelona-p02] Each district has its own council led by a city councillor.
[src:iucn-red-list/barcelona-p02] The composition of each district council depends on the number of votes each political party had in that district, so a district can be led by a councillor from a different party than the executive council.
[src:iucn-red-list/barcelona-p02] Barcelona has a well-developed higher education system of public universities.
[src:iucn-red-list/barcelona-p02] Most prominent among these are the University of Barcelona (established in 1450) and the more modern Pompeu Fabra University.
[src:iucn-red-list/barcelona-p02] Barcelona is also home to the Polytechnic University of Catalonia, and in the private sector the EADA Business School (founded in 1957), which became the first Barcelona institution to run manager training programmes for the business community.
[src:iucn-red-list/barcelona-p02] IESE Business School, as well as the largest private educational institution, the Ramon Llull University, which encompasses schools and institutes such as the ESADE Business School.
[src:iucn-red-list/barcelona-p02] The Autonomous University of Barcelona, another public university, is located in Bellaterra, a town in the Metropolitan Area.
[src:iucn-red-list/barcelona-p02] Toulouse Business School and the Open University of Catalonia (a private Internet-centred open university) are also based in Barcelona.
[src:iucn-red-list/barcelona-p02] The city has a network of public schools, from nurseries to high schools, under the responsibility of a consortium led by city council (though the curriculum is the responsibility of the Generalitat de Catalunya).
[src:iucn-red-list/barcelona-p02] There are also many private schools, some of them Roman Catholic.
[src:iucn-red-list/barcelona-p02] Most such schools receive a public subsidy on a per-student basis, are subject to inspection by the public authorities, and are required to follow the same curricular guidelines as public schools, though they charge tuition.
[src:iucn-red-list/barcelona-p02] Known as *escoles concertades*, they are distinct from schools whose funding is entirely private (*escoles privades*).
[src:iucn-red-list/barcelona-p02] The language of instruction at public schools and *escoles concertades* is Catalan, as stipulated by the 2009 Catalan Education Act.
[src:iucn-red-list/barcelona-p02] Spanish may be used as a language of instruction by teachers of Spanish literature or language, and foreign languages by teachers of those languages.
[src:iucn-red-list/barcelona-p02] An experimental partial immersion programme adopted by some schools allows for the teaching of a foreign language (English, generally) across the curriculum, though this is limited to a maximum of 30% of the school day.
[src:iucn-red-list/barcelona-p02] No public school or *escola concertada* in Barcelona may offer 50% or full immersion programmes in a foreign language, nor does any public school or *escola concertada* offer International Baccalaureate programmes.
[src:iucn-red-list/barcelona-p02] Barcelona's cultural roots go back 2000 years.
[src:iucn-red-list/barcelona-p02] Since the arrival of democracy, the Catalan language (very much repressed during the dictatorship of Franco) has been promoted, both by recovering works from the past and by stimulating the creation of new works.
[src:iucn-red-list/barcelona-p02] Barcelona is designated as a world-class city by the Globalization and World Cities Study Group and Network.
[src:iucn-red-list/barcelona-p02] It has also been part of the UNESCO Creative Cities Network as a City of Literature since 2015.
[src:iucn-red-list/barcelona-p02] Barcelona has many venues for live music and theatre, including the world-renowned Gran Teatre del Liceu opera house, the Teatre Nacional de Catalunya, the Teatre Lliure and the Palau de la Música Catalana concert hall.
[src:iucn-red-list/barcelona-p02] Barcelona also is home to the Barcelona Symphony and Catalonia National Orchestra (Orquestra Simfònica de Barcelona i Nacional de Catalunya, usually known as OBC), the largest symphonic orchestra in Catalonia.
[src:iucn-red-list/barcelona-p02] In 1999, the OBC inaugurated its new venue in the brand-new Auditorium (L'Auditori).
[src:iucn-red-list/barcelona-p02] It performs around 75 concerts per season and its current director is Eiji Oue.
[src:iucn-red-list/barcelona-p02] It is home to the Barcelona Guitar Orchestra, directed by Sergi Vicente.
[src:iucn-red-list/barcelona-p02] The major thoroughfare of La Rambla is home to mime artists and street performers.
[src:iucn-red-list/barcelona-p02] Yearly, two major pop music festivals take place in the city, the Sónar Festival and the Primavera Sound Festival.
[src:iucn-red-list/barcelona-p02] The city also has a thriving alternative music scene, with groups such as The Pinker Tones receiving international attention.
[src:iucn-red-list/barcelona-p02] Barcelona is an international hub of highly active and diverse nightlife with bars, dance bars and nightclubs staying open well past midnight.
[src:iucn-red-list/barcelona-p02] Barcelona's oldest and main online newspaper *VilaWeb* is also one of the oldest one in Europe (with Catalan and English editions).
[src:iucn-red-list/barcelona-p02] Several major FM stations include Catalunya Ràdio, RAC 1, RAC 105 and Cadena SER.
[src:iucn-red-list/barcelona-p02] Barcelona also has a local TV station, Betevé, owned by city council.
[src:iucn-red-list/barcelona-p02] The headquarters of Televisió de Catalunya, Catalonia's public network, are located in Sant Joan Despí, in Barcelona's metropolitan area.
[src:iucn-red-list/barcelona-p02] Barcelona has a long sporting tradition and hosted the highly successful 1992 Summer Olympics as well as several matches during the 1982 FIFA World Cup (at the two stadiums).
[src:iucn-red-list/barcelona-p02] It has hosted about 30 sports events of international significance.
[src:iucn-red-list/barcelona-p02] FC Barcelona is a sports club best known worldwide for its football team, one of the largest and the wealthiest in the world.
[src:iucn-red-list/barcelona-p02] It has 74 national trophies (while finishing 46 times as runners-up) and 17 continental prizes (with being runners-up 11 times), including five UEFA Champions League trophies out of eight finals and three FIFA Club World Cup wins out of four finals.
[src:iucn-red-list/barcelona-p02] The club won six trophies in a calendar year in 2009, becoming one of only 2 male football teams in the world to win the coveted sextuple, apart from FC Bayern Munich in 2020.
[src:iucn-red-list/barcelona-p02] The club's museum is the second most visited in Catalonia.
[src:iucn-red-list/barcelona-p02] The matches against cross-town rivals RCD Espanyol are of particular interest, but there are other Barcelonan football clubs in lower categories, like CE Europa and UE Sant Andreu.
[src:iucn-red-list/barcelona-p02] FC Barcelona's basketball team has a noted rivalry in the Liga ACB with nearby Joventut Badalona.
[src:iucn-red-list/barcelona-p02] Barcelona has three UEFA elite stadiums: FC Barcelona's Camp Nou, the largest stadium in Europe with a capacity of 99,354; the publicly owned Estadi Olímpic Lluís Companys, with a capacity of 55,926; used for the 1992 Olympics; and Estadi Cornellà-El Prat, with a capacity of 40,500.
[src:iucn-red-list/barcelona-p02] Furthermore, the city has several smaller stadiums such as Mini Estadi (also owned by FC Barcelona) with a capacity of 15,000, Camp Municipal Narcís Sala with a capacity of 6,563 and Nou Sardenya with a capacity of 7,000.
[src:iucn-red-list/barcelona-p02] The city has a further three multifunctional venues for sports and concerts: the Palau Sant Jordi with a capacity of 12,000 to 24,000 (depending on use), the Palau Blaugrana with a capacity of 7,500, and the Palau dels Esports de Barcelona with a capacity of 3,500.
[src:iucn-red-list/barcelona-p02] Barcelona was the host city for the 2013 World Aquatics Championships, which were held at the Palau San Jordi.
[src:iucn-red-list/barcelona-p02] There is also the Ultratrail Collserola which passes 85 km (53 mi) through the Collserola forest.
[src:iucn-red-list/barcelona-p02] The Open Seat Godó, a 50-year-old ATP World Tour 500 Series tennis tournament, is held annually in the facilities of the Real Club de Tenis Barcelona.
[src:iucn-red-list/barcelona-p02] Each year on Christmas Day, a 200-meter swimming race across the Old Port of Barcelona takes place.
[src:iucn-red-list/barcelona-p02] Near Barcelona, in Montmeló, the 107,000 capacity Circuit de Barcelona-Catalunya racetrack hosts the Formula One Spanish Grand Prix, the Catalan motorcycle Grand Prix, the Spanish GT Championship and races in the GP2 Series.
[src:iucn-red-list/barcelona-p02] Skateboarding and cycling are also very popular in Barcelona; in and around the city there are dozens of kilometers of bicycle paths.
[src:iucn-red-list/barcelona-p02] Barcelona is also home to numerous social centres and illegal squats that effectively form a shadow society mainly made up of the unemployed, immigrants, dropouts, anarchists, anti-authoritarians and autonomists.
[src:iucn-red-list/barcelona-p02] Peter Gelderloos estimates that there around 200 squatted buildings and 40 social centres across the city with thousands of inhabitants, making it one of the largest squatter movements in the world.
[src:iucn-red-list/barcelona-p02] He notes that they pirate electricity, internet and water allowing them to live on less than one euro a day.
[src:iucn-red-list/barcelona-p02] He argues that these squats embrace an anarcho-communist and anti-work philosophy, often freely fixing up new houses, cleaning, patching roofs, installing windows, toilets, showers, lights and kitchens.
[src:iucn-red-list/barcelona-p02] The squats help elderly residents avoid eviction and organize various protests throughout Barcelona.
[src:iucn-red-list/barcelona-p02] Notable squats include Can Vies, Can Masdeu, La Cinètika, Àgora Juan Andrés Benítez and Kasa de la Muntanya.
[src:iucn-red-list/barcelona-p02] Barcelona is served by Barcelona-El Prat Airport, about 17 km (11 mi) south-west of the centre of Barcelona.
[src:iucn-red-list/barcelona-p02] It is the second-largest airport in Spain, and the largest on the Mediterranean coast, which handled more than 50.17 million passengers in 2018, showing an annual upward trend.
[src:iucn-red-list/barcelona-p02] It is a main hub for Vueling Airlines and Ryanair, and also a focus for Iberia and Air Europa.
[src:iucn-red-list/barcelona-p02] The airport mainly serves domestic and European destinations, although some airlines offer destinations in Latin America, Asia and the United States.
[src:iucn-red-list/barcelona-p02] The airport is connected to the city by highway, metro (Airport T1 and Airport T2 stations), commuter train (Barcelona Airport railway station) and scheduled bus service.
[src:iucn-red-list/barcelona-p02] A new terminal (T1) has been built, and entered service on 17 June 2009.
[src:iucn-red-list/barcelona-p02] Some low-cost airlines, also use Girona-Costa Brava Airport, about 90 km (56 mi) to the north, Reus Airport, 77 km (48 mi) to the south, or Lleida-Alguaire Airport, about 150 km (93 mi) to the west, of the city.
[src:iucn-red-list/barcelona-p02] Sabadell Airport is a smaller airport in the nearby town of Sabadell, devoted to pilot training, aerotaxi and private flights.
[src:iucn-red-list/barcelona-p02] The city has several heliports, mainly at the top of hospitals or tall buildings.
[src:iucn-red-list/barcelona-p02] However, only one heliport is public, the Port of Barcelona Heliport.
[src:iucn-red-list/barcelona-p02] The Port of Barcelona has a 2000-year-old history and a great contemporary commercial importance.
[src:iucn-red-list/barcelona-p02] It is Europe's ninth largest container port, with a trade volume of 1.72 million TEU's in 2013.
[src:iucn-red-list/barcelona-p02] The port is managed by the Port Authority of Barcelona.
[src:iucn-red-list/barcelona-p02] Its 10 km2 (4 sq mi) are divided into three zones: Port Vell (the old port), the commercial port and the logistics port (Barcelona Free Port).
[src:iucn-red-list/barcelona-p02] The port is undergoing an enlargement that will double its size thanks to diverting the mouth of the Llobregat river 2 km (1 mi) to the south.
[src:iucn-red-list/barcelona-p02] The Barcelona harbour is the leading European cruiser port and a very important Mediterranean turnaround base.
[src:iucn-red-list/barcelona-p02] In 2013, 3.6 million pleasure cruise passengers used the Port of Barcelona.
[src:iucn-red-list/barcelona-p02] The Port Vell area also houses the Maremagnum (a commercial mall), a multiplex cinema, the IMAX Port Vell and one of Europe's largest aquariums – Aquarium Barcelona, containing 8,000 fish and 11 sharks contained in 22 basins filled with 4 million litres of sea water.
[src:iucn-red-list/barcelona-p02] The Maremagnum, being situated within the confines of the port, is the only commercial mall in the city that can open on Sundays and public holidays.
[src:iucn-red-list/barcelona-p02] Barcelona is a major hub for the Spanish rail network.
[src:iucn-red-list/barcelona-p02] The city's main Inter-city rail station is Barcelona Sants railway station, whilst Estació de França terminus serves a secondary role handling suburban, regional and medium distance services.
[src:iucn-red-list/barcelona-p02] Freight services operate to local industries and to the Port of Barcelona.
[src:iucn-red-list/barcelona-p02] RENFE's AVE high-speed rail system, which is designed for speeds of 310 km/h (193 mph), was extended from Madrid to Barcelona in 2008 in the form of the Madrid–Barcelona high-speed rail line.
[src:iucn-red-list/barcelona-p02] A shared RENFE-SNCF high-speed rail connecting Barcelona and France (Paris, Marseille and Toulouse, through Perpignan–Barcelona high-speed rail line) was launched in 2013.
[src:iucn-red-list/barcelona-p02] Both these lines serve Barcelona Sants terminal station.
[src:iucn-red-list/barcelona-p02] Barcelona is served by an extensive local public transport network that includes a metro system, a bus network, a regional railway system, trams, funiculars, rack railways, a Gondola lift and aerial cable cars.
[src:iucn-red-list/barcelona-p02] These networks and lines are run by a number of different operators but they are integrated into a coordinated fare system, administered by the Autoritat del Transport Metropolità (ATM).
[src:iucn-red-list/barcelona-p02] The system is divided into fare zones (1 to 6) and various Integrated Travel Cards are available.
[src:iucn-red-list/barcelona-p02] The Barcelona Metro network comprises twelve lines, identified by an "L" followed by the line number as well as by individual colours.
[src:iucn-red-list/barcelona-p02] The Metro largely runs underground; eight Metro lines are operated on dedicated track by the Transports Metropolitans de Barcelona (TMB), whilst four lines are operated by the Ferrocarrils de la Generalitat de Catalunya (FGC) and some of them share tracks with RENFE commuter lines.
[src:iucn-red-list/barcelona-p02] In addition to the city Metro, several regional rail lines operated by Renfe's Rodalies de Catalunya and FGC run across the city, providing connections to outlying towns in the surrounding region.
[src:iucn-red-list/barcelona-p02] The city currently has two modern tram systems, Trambaix and Trambesòs, are operated by TramMet.
[src:iucn-red-list/barcelona-p02] Both go through the Avinguda Diagonal, one at each end of the avenue, but they do not meet.
[src:iucn-red-list/barcelona-p02] Since 2020, there is an ongoing project to unify the two systems and allow the tram to connect both ends of the city.
[src:iucn-red-list/barcelona-p02] A heritage tram line, the Tramvia Blau, also operates between the metro Line 7 and the Funicular del Tibidabo.
[src:iucn-red-list/barcelona-p02] Barcelona's metro and rail system is supplemented by several aerial cable cars, funiculars and rack railways that provide connections to mountain-top stations.
[src:iucn-red-list/barcelona-p02] FGC operates the Funicular de Tibidabo up the hill of Tibidabo and the Funicular de Vallvidrera, while TMB runs the Funicular de Montjuïc up Montjuïc.
[src:iucn-red-list/barcelona-p02] The city has two aerial cable cars: the Montjuïc Cable Car, which serves Montjuïc castle, and the Port Vell Aerial Tramway that runs via Torre Jaume I and Torre Sant Sebastià over the port.
[src:iucn-red-list/barcelona-p02] Buses in Barcelona are a major form of public transport, with extensive local, interurban and night bus networks.
[src:iucn-red-list/barcelona-p02] Most local services are operated by the TMB, although some other services are operated by a number of private companies, albeit still within the ATM fare structure.
[src:iucn-red-list/barcelona-p02] There are 21 night lines, 19 of them go through Plaça de Catalunya, where you can change to other lines.
[src:iucn-red-list/barcelona-p02] A separate private bus line, known as Aerobús, links the airport with the city centre, with its own fare structure.
[src:iucn-red-list/barcelona-p02] The Estació del Nord (Northern Station), a former railway station which was renovated for the 1992 Olympic Games, now serves as the terminus for long-distance and regional bus services.
[src:iucn-red-list/barcelona-p02] Barcelona has a metered taxi fleet governed by the Institut Metropolità del Taxi (Metropolitan Taxi Institute), composed of more than 10,000 cars.
[src:iucn-red-list/barcelona-p02] Most of the licences are in the hands of self-employed drivers.
[src:iucn-red-list/barcelona-p02] With their black and yellow livery, Barcelona's taxis are easily spotted, and can be caught from one of many taxi ranks, hailed on street, called by telephone or via app.
[src:iucn-red-list/barcelona-p02] On 22 March 2007, Barcelona's City Council started the Bicing service, a bicycle service understood as a public transport.
[src:iucn-red-list/barcelona-p02] Once the user has their user card, they can take a bicycle from any of the more than 400 stations spread around the city and use it anywhere the urban area of the city, and then leave it at another station.
[src:iucn-red-list/barcelona-p02] The service has been a success, with 50,000 subscribed users in three months.
[src:iucn-red-list/barcelona-p02] Barcelona lies on three international routes, including European route E15 that follows the Mediterranean coast, European route E90 to Madrid and Lisbon, and European route E09 to Paris.
[src:iucn-red-list/barcelona-p02] It is also served by a comprehensive network of motorways and highways throughout the metropolitan area, including A-2, A-7/AP-7, C-16, C-17, C-31, C-32, C-33, C-60.
[src:iucn-red-list/barcelona-p02] The city's main arteries include Diagonal Avenue, which crosses it diagonally, Meridiana Avenue which leads to Glòries and connects with Diagonal Avenue and Gran Via de les Corts Catalanes, which crosses the city from east to west, passing through its centre.
[src:iucn-red-list/barcelona-p02] The famous boulevard of La Rambla, whilst no longer an important vehicular route, remains an important pedestrian route.
[src:iucn-red-list/barcelona-p02] The *Barri Gòtic* (Catalan for "Gothic Quarter") is the centre of the old city of Barcelona.
[src:iucn-red-list/barcelona-p02] Many of the buildings date from medieval times, some from as far back as the Roman settlement of Barcelona.
[src:iucn-red-list/barcelona-p02] Catalan *modernista* architecture (related to the movement known as Art Nouveau in the rest of Europe) developed between 1885 and 1950 and left an important legacy in Barcelona.
[src:iucn-red-list/barcelona-p02] Several of these buildings are World Heritage Sites.
[src:iucn-red-list/barcelona-p02] Especially remarkable is the work of architect Antoni Gaudí, which can be seen throughout the city.
[src:iucn-red-list/barcelona-p02] His best-known work is the immense but still unfinished church of the Sagrada Família, which has been under construction since 1882 and is still financed by private donations.
[src:iucn-red-list/barcelona-p02] As of 2015, completion is planned for 2026.
[src:iucn-red-list/barcelona-p02] Barcelona was also home to Mies van der Rohe's Barcelona Pavilion.
[src:iucn-red-list/barcelona-p02] Designed in 1929 for the International Exposition for Germany, it was an iconic building that came to symbolize modern architecture as the embodiment of van der Rohe's aphorisms "less is more" and "God is in the details".
[src:iucn-red-list/barcelona-p02] The Barcelona pavilion was intended as a temporary structure and was torn down in 1930 less than a year after it was constructed.
[src:iucn-red-list/barcelona-p02] A modern re-creation by Spanish architects now stands in Barcelona, however, constructed in 1986.
[src:iucn-red-list/barcelona-p02] Barcelona won the 1999 RIBA Royal Gold Medal for its architecture, the first (and as of 2015, only) time that the winner has been a city rather than an individual architect.
[src:iucn-red-list/barcelona-p02] Barcelona has many museums, which cover different areas and eras.
[src:iucn-red-list/barcelona-p02] The National Museum of Art of Catalonia possesses a well-known collection of Romanesque art, while the Barcelona Museum of Contemporary Art focuses on post-1945 Catalan and Spanish art.
[src:iucn-red-list/barcelona-p02] The Fundació Joan Miró, Picasso Museum, and Fundació Antoni Tàpies hold important collections of these world-renowned artists, as well as the Can Framis Museum, focused on post-1960 Catalan Art owned by Fundació Vila Casas.
[src:iucn-red-list/barcelona-p02] The Erotic museum of Barcelona is among the most peculiar ones, while CosmoCaixa is a science museum that received the European Museum of the Year Award in 2006.
[src:iucn-red-list/barcelona-p02] The Museum of Mathematics of Catalonia is a place where mathematics is approached from a practical and playful point of view.
[src:iucn-red-list/barcelona-p02] The Museum of Natural Sciences of Barcelona was founded in 1882 under the name of "Museo Martorell de Arqueología y Ciencias Naturales" (Spanish for "Martorell Museum of Archaeology and Natural Sciences").
[src:iucn-red-list/barcelona-p02] Those two gardens are a part of the Botanical Institute of Barcelona too.
[src:iucn-red-list/barcelona-p02] The FC Barcelona Museum is the third most popular tourist attraction in Catalonia, with 1,51 million visitors in 2013.
[src:iucn-red-list/barcelona-p02] Barcelona contains sixty municipal parks, twelve of which are historic, five of which are thematic (botanical), forty-five of which are urban, and six of which are forest.
[src:iucn-red-list/barcelona-p02] They range from vest-pocket parks to large recreation areas.
[src:iucn-red-list/barcelona-p02] The urban parks alone cover 10% of the city (549.7 ha or 1,358.3 acres).
[src:iucn-red-list/barcelona-p02] The total park surface grows about 10 ha (25 acres) per year, with a proportion of 18.1 m2 (195 sq ft) of park area per inhabitant.
[src:iucn-red-list/barcelona-p02] Of Barcelona's parks, Montjuïc is the largest, with 203 ha located on the mountain of the same name, and includes the Botanical Garden of Barcelona, the Mossèn Costa i Llobera Gardens, and more.
[src:iucn-red-list/barcelona-p02] There are also several smaller parks, for example, the Parc de Les Aigües (2 ha or 4.9 acres).
[src:iucn-red-list/barcelona-p02] A part of the Collserola Park is also within the city limits.
[src:iucn-red-list/barcelona-p02] PortAventura World, one of the largest resort in Europe, with 5,837,509 visitors per year, is located one hour's drive from Barcelona.
[src:iucn-red-list/barcelona-p02] Also, within the city lies Tibidabo Amusement Park, a smaller amusement park in Plaza del Tibidabo, with the Muntanya Russa amusement ride.
[src:iucn-red-list/barcelona-p02] Besides the parks managed by the town hall, there exist several self-managed green spaces and gardens such as Jardí del Silenci in Gracia, the Ágora Juan Andrés Benítez in Raval, and L'Horta Alliberada in Sants.
[src:iucn-red-list/barcelona-p02] Barcelona beach was listed as number one in a list of the top ten city beaches in the world according to *National Geographic* and *Discovery Channel*.
[src:iucn-red-list/barcelona-p02] Barcelona contains seven beaches, totalling 4.5 km (2+3⁄4 mi) of coastline.
[src:iucn-red-list/barcelona-p02] Sant Sebastià, Barceloneta and Somorrostro beaches, both 1,100 m (3,610 ft) in length, are the largest, oldest and the most-frequented beaches in Barcelona.
[src:iucn-red-list/barcelona-p02] The Olympic Harbour separates them from the other city beaches: Nova Icària, Bogatell, Mar Bella, Nova Mar Bella and Llevant.
[src:iucn-red-list/barcelona-p02] These beaches (ranging from 400 to 640 m (1,310 to 2,100 ft) were opened as a result of the city restructuring to host the 1992 Summer Olympics, when a great number of industrial buildings were demolished.
[src:iucn-red-list/barcelona-p02] At present, the beach sand is artificially replenished given that storms regularly remove large quantities of material.
[src:iucn-red-list/barcelona-p02] The 2004 Universal Forum of Cultures left the city a large concrete bathing zone on the eastmost part of the city's coastline.
[src:iucn-red-list/barcelona-p02] Most recently, Llevant is the first beach to allow dogs access during summer season.
[src:iucn-red-list/biodiversity-action-plan] A **biodiversity action plan** (**BAP**) is an internationally recognized program aimed at protecting and restoring threatened species and habitats, and at strengthening the resilience of biological systems.
[src:iucn-red-list/biodiversity-action-plan] The concept emerged from the 1992 Convention on Biological Diversity (CBD), which called on participating nations to develop strategies for conserving biodiversity.
[src:iucn-red-list/biodiversity-action-plan] As of 2009, 191 countries had ratified the CBD, although only a portion of them had produced comprehensive BAP documents.
[src:iucn-red-list/biodiversity-action-plan] A fundamental method of engagement to a BAP is thorough documentation regarding individual species, with emphasis upon the population distribution and conservation status.
[src:iucn-red-list/biodiversity-action-plan] This task, while fundamental, is highly daunting, since only an estimated ten percent of the world's species are believed to have been characterized as of 2006, most of these unknowns being fungi, invertebrate animals, micro-organisms and plants.
[src:iucn-red-list/biodiversity-action-plan] For many bird, mammal and reptile species, information is often available in published literature; however, for fungi, invertebrate animals, micro-organisms and many plants, such information may require considerable local data collection.
[src:iucn-red-list/biodiversity-action-plan] It is also useful to compile time trends of population estimates in order to understand the dynamics of population variability and vulnerability.
[src:iucn-red-list/biodiversity-action-plan] In some parts of the world complete species inventories are not realistic; for example, in the Madagascar dry deciduous forests, many species are completely undocumented and much of the region has never even been systematically explored by scientists.
[src:iucn-red-list/biodiversity-action-plan] A species plan component of a country's BAP should ideally entail a thorough description of the range, habitat, behaviour, breeding and interaction with other species.
[src:iucn-red-list/biodiversity-action-plan] Once a determination has been made of conservation status (e.g. rare, endangered, threatened, vulnerable), a plan can then be created to conserve and restore the species population to target levels.
[src:iucn-red-list/biodiversity-action-plan] The plan should also articulate which public and private agencies should implement the protection strategy and indicate budgets available to execute this strategy.
[src:iucn-red-list/biodiversity-action-plan] Agricultural practices can reduce the biodiversity of a region significantly.
[src:iucn-red-list/biodiversity-action-plan] Biodiversity Action Plans for agricultural production are necessary to ensure a biodiversity friendly production.
[src:iucn-red-list/biodiversity-action-plan] It has not been common for companies to integrate biodiversity aspects into their value chain, but some companies and organizations have shown overall efforts for implementing better practices.
[src:iucn-red-list/biodiversity-action-plan] An existing example for guidelines on biodiversity practices in agriculture is the Biodiversity Action Plan for spice production in India.
[src:iucn-red-list/biodiversity-action-plan] By planning and implementing biodiversity friendly measures, farmers can mitigate negative impacts and support positive influences.
[src:iucn-red-list/biodiversity-action-plan] Where a number of threatened species depend upon a specific habitat, it may be appropriate to prepare a habitat protection element of the Biodiversity Action Plan.
[src:iucn-red-list/biodiversity-action-plan] Examples of such special habitats are: raised acidic bogs of Scotland; Waterberg Biosphere bushveld in South Africa; California's coastal wetlands; and Sweden's Stora Alvaret on the island of Öland.
[src:iucn-red-list/biodiversity-action-plan] In this case also, careful inventories of species and also the geographic extent and quality of the habitat must be documented.
[src:iucn-red-list/biodiversity-action-plan] Then, as with species plans, a program can be created to protect, enhance and/or restore habitat using similar strategies as discussed above under the species plans.
[src:iucn-red-list/biodiversity-action-plan] Some examples of individual countries which have produced substantive Biodiversity Action Plans follow.
[src:iucn-red-list/biodiversity-action-plan] In every example the plans concentrate on plants and vertebrate animals, with very little attention to neglected groups such as fungi, invertebrate animals and micro-organisms, even though these are also part of biodiversity.
[src:iucn-red-list/biodiversity-action-plan] Preparation of a country BAP may cost up to 100 million pounds sterling, with annual maintenance costs roughly ten percent of the initial cost.
[src:iucn-red-list/biodiversity-action-plan] If plans took into account neglected groups, the cost would be higher.
[src:iucn-red-list/biodiversity-action-plan] Obviously costs for countries with small geographical area or simplified ecosystems have a much lesser cost.
[src:iucn-red-list/biodiversity-action-plan] Lucia BAP has been costed in the area of several million pounds sterling.
[src:iucn-red-list/biodiversity-action-plan] Australia has developed a detailed and rigorous Biodiversity Action Plan.
[src:iucn-red-list/biodiversity-action-plan] This document estimates that the total number of indigenous species may be 560,000, many of which are endemic.
[src:iucn-red-list/biodiversity-action-plan] A key element of the BAP is protection of the Great Barrier Reef, which is actually in a much higher state of health than most of the world's reefs, Australia having one of the highest percentages of treated wastewater.
[src:iucn-red-list/biodiversity-action-plan] There are however serious ongoing concerns, particularly in regards to the ongoing negative impact on water quality from land use practices.
[src:iucn-red-list/biodiversity-action-plan] Also, climate change impact is feared to be significant.
[src:iucn-red-list/biodiversity-action-plan] Considerable analysis has been conducted on the sustainable yield of firewood production, a major threat to deforestation in most tropical countries.
[src:iucn-red-list/biodiversity-action-plan] Biological inventory work; assessment of harvesting practices; and computer modeling of the dynamics of treefall, rot and harvest; have been carried out to adduce data on safe harvesting rates.
[src:iucn-red-list/biodiversity-action-plan] Extensive research has also been conducted on the relation of brush clearance to biodiversity decline and impact on water tables; for example, these effects have been analyzed in the Toolibin Lake wetlands region.
[src:iucn-red-list/biodiversity-action-plan] New Zealand has ratified the Convention on Biological Diversity and as part of The New Zealand Biodiversity Strategy and Biodiversity Action Plans are implemented on ten separate themes.
[src:iucn-red-list/biodiversity-action-plan] Local government and some companies also have their own Biodiversity Action Plan.
[src:iucn-red-list/biodiversity-action-plan] Lucia BAP recognizes impacts of large numbers of tourists to the marine and coastal diversity of the Soufrière area of the country.
[src:iucn-red-list/biodiversity-action-plan] The BAP specifically acknowledges that the carrying capacity for human use and water pollution discharge of sensitive reef areas was exceeded by the year 1990.
[src:iucn-red-list/biodiversity-action-plan] The plan also addresses conservation of the historic island fishing industry.
[src:iucn-red-list/biodiversity-action-plan] In 1992, several institutions in conjunction with native fishermen to produce a sustainable management plan for fishery resources, embodied in the Soufrière Marine Management Area.
[src:iucn-red-list/biodiversity-action-plan] Lucia BAP features significant involvement from the University of the West Indies.
[src:iucn-red-list/biodiversity-action-plan] Specific detailed attention is given to three species of threatened marine turtles, to a variety of vulnerable birds and a number of pelagic fishes and cetaceans.
[src:iucn-red-list/biodiversity-action-plan] In terms of habitat conservation the plan focusses attention on the biologically productive mangrove swamps and notes that virtually all mangrove areas had already come under national protection by 1984.
[src:iucn-red-list/biodiversity-action-plan] The Tanzania national BAP addresses issues related to sustainable use of Lake Manyara, an extensive freshwater lake, whose usage by humans accelerated in the period 1950 to 1990.
[src:iucn-red-list/biodiversity-action-plan] The designation of the Lake Manyara Biosphere Reserve under UNESCO's Man and the Biosphere Programme in 1981 combines conservation of the lake and surrounding high value forests with sustainable use of the wetlands area and simple agriculture.
[src:iucn-red-list/biodiversity-action-plan] This BAP has united principal lake users in establishing management targets.
[src:iucn-red-list/biodiversity-action-plan] The biosphere reserve has induced sustainable management of the wetlands, including monitoring groundwater and the chemistry of the escarpment water source.
[src:iucn-red-list/biodiversity-action-plan] The United Kingdom Biodiversity Action Plan covers not only terrestrial species associated with lands within the UK, but also marine species and migratory birds, which spend a limited time in the UK or its offshore waters.
[src:iucn-red-list/biodiversity-action-plan] The UK plan encompasses "391 Species Action Plans, 45 Habitat Action Plans and 162 Local Biodiversity Action Plans with targeted actions".
[src:iucn-red-list/biodiversity-action-plan] This plan is noteworthy because of its extensive detail, clarity of endangerment mechanisms, specificity of actions, follow up monitoring program and its inclusion of migrating cetaceans and pelagic birds.
[src:iucn-red-list/biodiversity-action-plan] On August 28, 2007, the new Biodiversity Action Plan (BAP) [launched in 1997] identified 1,149 species and 65 habitats in the UK that needed conservation and greater protection.
[src:iucn-red-list/biodiversity-action-plan] The updated list included the hedgehog, house sparrow, grass snake and the garden tiger moth, while otters, bottlenose dolphins and red squirrels remained in need of habitat protection.
[src:iucn-red-list/biodiversity-action-plan] In May 2011, the European Commission adopted a new strategy to halt the loss of biodiversity and ecosystem services in the EU by 2020, in line with the commitments made at the 10th meeting of the Convention on Biological Diversity (CBD) held in Nagoya, Japan in 2010.
[src:iucn-red-list/biodiversity-action-plan] In 2012 the UK BAP was succeeded by the 'UK Post-2010 Biodiversity Framework'.
[src:iucn-red-list/biodiversity-action-plan] To support the work of the UK BAP, the UK BAP website was created by JNCC in 2001.
[src:iucn-red-list/biodiversity-action-plan] The website contained information on the BAP process, hosted all relevant documents, and provided news and relevant updates.
[src:iucn-red-list/biodiversity-action-plan] In March 2011, as part of the UK government's review of websites, the UK BAP site was ‘closed’, and the core content was migrated into the JNCC website.
[src:iucn-red-list/biodiversity-action-plan] Content from the original UK BAP website has been archived by the National Archives as snapshots from various dates (for example, UK *BAP*: copy March 2011; copy 2012).
[src:iucn-red-list/biodiversity-action-plan] Twenty-six years prior to the international biodiversity convention, the United States had launched a national program to protect threatened species in the form of the 1966 Endangered Species Act.
[src:iucn-red-list/biodiversity-action-plan] The legislation created broad authority for analyzing and listing species of concern, and mandated that Species Recovery Plans be created.
[src:iucn-red-list/biodiversity-action-plan] Thus, while the USA is an unratified signer of the accord, arguably it has the longest track record and most comprehensive program of species protection of any country.
[src:iucn-red-list/biodiversity-action-plan] There are about 7000 listed species (e.g. endangered or threatened), of which about half have approved Recovery Plans.
[src:iucn-red-list/biodiversity-action-plan] While this number of species seems high compared to other countries, the value is rather indicative of the total number of species characterized, which is extremely large.
[src:iucn-red-list/biodiversity-action-plan] Five major divisions of habitat have been identified in Uzbekistan’s BAP: Wetlands (including reed habitat and man-made marsh); desert ecosystems (including sandy, stony and clay); steppes; riparian ecosystems; and mountain ecosystems.
[src:iucn-red-list/biodiversity-action-plan] Over 27,000 species have been inventoried in the country, with a high rate of endemism for fishes and reptiles.
[src:iucn-red-list/biodiversity-action-plan] Principal threats to biodiversity are related to human activities associated with overpopulation and generally related to agricultural intensification.
[src:iucn-red-list/biodiversity-action-plan] Major geographic regions encompassed by the BAP include the Aral Sea Programme (threatened by long-term drainage and salination, largely for cotton production), the Nuratau Biosphere Reserve, and the Western Tien Shan Mountains Programme (in conjunction with Kazakhstan and Kyrgyzstan).
[src:iucn-red-list/biodiversity-action-plan] Some developing countries criticize the emphasis of BAPs, because these plans inherently favour consideration of wildlife protection above food and industrial production, and in some cases may represent an obstacle to population growth.
[src:iucn-red-list/biodiversity-action-plan] The plans are costly to produce, a fact which makes it difficult for many smaller countries and poorer countries to comply.
[src:iucn-red-list/biodiversity-action-plan] In terms of the plans themselves, many countries have adopted pro-forma plans including little research and even less in the way of natural resource management.
[src:iucn-red-list/biodiversity-action-plan] Almost universally, this has resulted in plans which emphasize plants and vertebrate animals, and which overlook fungi, invertebrate animals and micro-organisms.
[src:iucn-red-list/biodiversity-action-plan] With regard to specific world regions, there is a notable lack of substantive participation by most of the Middle Eastern countries and much of Africa, the latter of which may be impeded by economic considerations of plan preparation.
[src:iucn-red-list/biodiversity-action-plan] Some governments such as the European Union have diverted the purpose of a biodiversity action plan, and implemented the convention accord by a set of economic development policies with referencing certain ecosystems' protection.
[src:iucn-red-list/biodiversity-action-plan] The definition of biodiversity under the Convention on Biological Diversity now recognises that biodiversity is a combination of ecosystem structure and function, as much as its components e.g. species, habitats and genetic resources.
[src:iucn-red-list/biodiversity-action-plan] Biodiversity and wildlife are not the same thing.
[src:iucn-red-list/biodiversity-action-plan] The traditional focus on threatened species in BAPs is at odds with the principles of biodiversity management because, by the time species become threatened, the processes that maintain biodiversity are already compromised.
[src:iucn-red-list/biodiversity-action-plan] Individual species are also regarded as generally poor indicators of biodiversity when it comes to actual planning.
[src:iucn-red-list/biodiversity-action-plan] A species approach to BAPs only serves to identify and at best, apply a patch to existing problems.
[src:iucn-red-list/biodiversity-action-plan] Increasingly, biodiversity planners are looking through the lens of ecosystem services.
[src:iucn-red-list/biodiversity-action-plan] Critics of biodiversity are often confusing the need to protect species (their intrinsic value) with the need to maintain ecosystem processes, which ultimately maintain human society and do not compromise economic development.
[src:iucn-red-list/biodiversity-action-plan] Hence, a core principle of biodiversity management, that traditional BAPs overlook, is the need to incorporate cultural, social and economic values in the process.
[src:iucn-red-list/biodiversity-action-plan] Modern day BAPs use an analysis of ecosystem services, key ecological process drivers, and use species as one of many indicators of change.
[src:iucn-red-list/biodiversity-action-plan] They would seek to maintain structure and function by addressing habitat connectivity and resilience and may look at communities of species (threatened or otherwise) as one method of monitoring outcomes.
[src:iucn-red-list/biodiversity-action-plan] Ultimately, species are the litmus test for biodiversity – viable populations of species can only be expected to exist in relatively intact habitats.
[src:iucn-red-list/biodiversity-action-plan] However, the rationale behind BAPs is to "conserve and restore" biodiversity.
[src:iucn-red-list/biodiversity-action-plan] One of the fastest developing areas of management is biodiversity offsets.
[src:iucn-red-list/biodiversity-action-plan] The principles are in keeping with ecological impact assessment, which in turn depends on good quality BAPs for evaluation.
[src:iucn-red-list/biodiversity-action-plan] Contemporary principles of biodiversity management, such as those produced by the Business Biodiversity Offsets Program are now integral to any plans to manage biodiversity, including the development of BAPs.
[src:iucn-red-list/biodiversity-heritage-library] The **Biodiversity Heritage Library** (**BHL**) is the world’s largest open-access digital library for biodiversity literature and archives.
[src:iucn-red-list/biodiversity-heritage-library] The BHL consortium works with the international taxonomic community, publishers, bioinformaticians, and information technology professionals to develop tools and services to facilitate greater access, interoperability, and reuse of content and data.
[src:iucn-red-list/biodiversity-heritage-library] BHL provides a range of services, data exports, and APIs to allow users to download content, harvest source data files, and reuse materials for research purposes.
[src:iucn-red-list/biodiversity-heritage-library] Through taxonomic intelligence tools developed by Global Names Architecture, BHL indexes the taxonomic names throughout the collection, allowing researchers to locate publications about specific taxa.
[src:iucn-red-list/biodiversity-heritage-library] In partnership with the Internet Archive and through local digitization efforts, BHL's portal provides free access to hundreds of thousands of volumes, comprising over 59 million pages, from the 15th–21st centuries.
[src:iucn-red-list/biodiversity-heritage-library] Founded in 2006, BHL soon became the third broad digitization project for biodiversity literature, after Gallica and AnimalBase.
[src:iucn-red-list/biodiversity-heritage-library] In 2008, the size of Gallica and AnimalBase was passed, and BHL is now by far the world's largest digitization project for biodiversity literature.
[src:iucn-red-list/biodiversity-heritage-library] It was the literature cornerstone of the *Encyclopedia of Life*.
[src:iucn-red-list/biodiversity-heritage-library] Initially, the Biodiversity Heritage Library was a collaboration of ten natural history and botanical libraries and currently it has fourteen members.
[src:iucn-red-list/biodiversity-heritage-library] Since 2009, the BHL has expanded globally.
[src:iucn-red-list/biodiversity-heritage-library] The European Commission's eContentPlus program has funded the as Biodiversity Heritage Library for Europe.
[src:iucn-red-list/biodiversity-heritage-library] The BHL Europe project consisted of 28 consortium partners, mostly European libraries.
[src:iucn-red-list/biodiversity-heritage-library] The project closed in 2012, but many participating institutions remain active as BHL partners.
[src:iucn-red-list/biodiversity-heritage-library] Shortly thereafter another project BHL-China was launched in Beijing, in collaboration with the Chinese Academy of Sciences.
[src:iucn-red-list/biodiversity-heritage-library] Since then BHL in the strict sense has been called BHL-US/UK (usually only BHL-US), the global project has been referred to as BHL-Global, to distinguish it from the US/UK project.
[src:iucn-red-list/biodiversity-heritage-library] The global BHL project is managed primarily by the Smithsonian Institution (Washington, D.C.), Natural History Museum (London), and Missouri Botanical Garden.
[src:iucn-red-list/biodiversity-heritage-library] In 2010, the Atlas of Living Australia created a regional node for Australia.
[src:iucn-red-list/biodiversity-heritage-library] The digitisation operation is hosted by Museums Victoria and is nationally funded by the ALA.
[src:iucn-red-list/biodiversity-heritage-library] Australia's museums, herbaria, royal societies, field naturalist clubs and government organisations make up the contributors.
[src:iucn-red-list/biodiversity-heritage-library] Additionally, Brazil (through SciELO), and the Bibliotheca Alexandrina have also created regional BHL nodes.
[src:iucn-red-list/biodiversity-heritage-library] These projects will work together to share content, protocols, services, and digital preservation practices.
[src:iucn-red-list/biodiversity-heritage-library] There is an online BHL portal featuring Google Maps API integration, AJAX, tag clouds, and JPEG2000 images that facilitate multi-resolution zoom and pan.
[src:iucn-red-list/biodiversity-heritage-library] The Biodiversity Heritage Library is managed by a Secretariat headquartered at Smithsonian Libraries and Archives in Washington, DC.
[src:iucn-red-list/biodiversity-heritage-library] An Executive Committee, elected by Biodiversity Heritage Library Members, provides strategic direction.
[src:iucn-red-list/biodiversity-heritage-library] The Secretariat is led by the BHL Program Director.
[src:iucn-red-list/biodiversity-heritage-library] Thomas Garnett served in that position (2006–2012) and was succeeded by Martin R.
[src:iucn-red-list/biodiversity-heritage-library] Kelli Trei (Biosciences Librarian and Associate Professor from the University of Illinois Urbana-Champaign) was appointed Transition Director in May 2025.
[src:iucn-red-list/biodiversity-heritage-library] The Biodiversity Heritage Library was awarded the 2010 John Thackray Medal of the Society for the History of Natural History.
[src:iucn-red-list/biodiversity-heritage-library] This award "recognizes significant achievements in the history or bibliography of natural history".
[src:iucn-red-list/biodiversity-heritage-library] In March 2012, the Missouri Botanical Garden received $260,000 in funding from the National Endowment for the Humanities to identify and describe natural history illustrations from the digitized books and journals in the online Biodiversity Heritage Library.
[src:iucn-red-list/biodiversity-heritage-library] The Art of Life project will develop software tools for automated identification and description of visual resources contained within the more than 100,000 volumes and 38 million pages of core historic literature made available through BHL digitization activities.
[src:iucn-red-list/biodiversity-heritage-library] IDG's Computerworld Honors Program announced on March 19, 2013 the Biodiversity Heritage Library as a 2013 laureate.
[src:iucn-red-list/biodiversity-heritage-library] The annual award program honors visionary applications of information technology promoting positive social, economic, and educational change.
[src:iucn-red-list/biodiversity-heritage-library] In May 2013, the Biodiversity Heritage Library was the recipient of the Charles Robert Long Award of Extraordinary Merit from the Council on Botanical and Horticultural Libraries.
[src:iucn-red-list/biodiversity-heritage-library] The award is the highest honor bestowed by the council, honoring outstanding contributions and meritorious service to the field of botanical and horticultural literature, with only 14 recipients named since 1988.
[src:iucn-red-list/biodiversity-heritage-library] In October 2015, the Biodiversity Heritage Library was awarded the Internet Archive’s Internet Heroes at the 2015 Library Leaders’ Forum in San Francisco, 21–23 October 2015.
[src:iucn-red-list/biodiversity-heritage-library] The Digital Library Federation named the Biodiversity Heritage Library a joint winner (along with the American Archive of Public Broadcasting) of the DLF 2016 Community/Capacity Award.
[src:iucn-red-list/biodiversity-heritage-library] The award recognizes collection action over individual achievement and honors community-minded capacity building in digital libraries, archives and museums.
[src:iucn-red-list/biodiversity-heritage-library] In appreciation of the services to taxonomists, a species of snail from Laos was named *Vargapupa biheli* in 2015, the species name derived from the initials BHL.
[src:iucn-red-list/biodiversity-heritage-library] A second species, a new species of fossil robber fly, *Kishenehnoasilus bhl* was named after the Biodiversity Heritage Library in 2019.
[src:iucn-red-list/biodiversity-heritage-library] The primary funding for the Biodiversity Heritage Library came via the Encyclopedia of Life through a grant from the John D. and Catherine T.
[src:iucn-red-list/biodiversity-heritage-library] Additional grants have been received from The Gordon and Betty Moore Foundation, The Richard Lounsbery Foundation, the Institute of Museum and Library Services (IMLS).
[src:iucn-red-list/biodiversity-heritage-library] The Council on Library and Information Resources (CLIR) awarded the Biodiversity Heritage Library funding in 2015 as part of the Digitizing Hidden Special Collections and Archives program $491,713 to support increased accessibility to original scientific documentation found in archival field notes.
[src:iucn-red-list/biodiversity-heritage-library] Members of the Biodiversity Heritage Library also have received generous support from their parent institutions.
[src:iucn-red-list/biodiversity-heritage-library] In addition to staffing and other costs, direct contributions have included the Atherton Seidell Endowment Fund by the Smithsonian Institution.
[src:iucn-red-list/biodiversity-p01] Since life began on Earth, six major mass extinctions and several minor events have led to large and sudden drops in biodiversity.
[src:iucn-red-list/biodiversity-p01] The Phanerozoic aeon (the last 540 million years) marked a rapid growth in biodiversity via the Cambrian explosion.
[src:iucn-red-list/biodiversity-p01] In this period, the majority of multicellular phyla first appeared.
[src:iucn-red-list/biodiversity-p01] The next 400 million years included repeated, massive biodiversity losses.
[src:iucn-red-list/biodiversity-p01] Those events have been classified as mass extinction events.
[src:iucn-red-list/biodiversity-p01] In the Carboniferous, rainforest collapse may have led to a great loss of plant and animal life.
[src:iucn-red-list/biodiversity-p01] The Permian–Triassic extinction event, 251 million years ago, was the worst; vertebrate recovery took 30 million years.
[src:iucn-red-list/biodiversity-p01] Human activities have led to an ongoing biodiversity loss and an accompanying loss of genetic diversity.
[src:iucn-red-list/biodiversity-p01] This process is often referred to as Holocene extinction, or the *sixth mass extinction*.
[src:iucn-red-list/biodiversity-p01] For example, it was estimated in 2007 that up to 30% of all species will be extinct by 2050.
[src:iucn-red-list/biodiversity-p01] Destroying habitats for farming is a key reason why biodiversity is decreasing today.
[src:iucn-red-list/biodiversity-p01] This can be seen for example in the effects of climate change on biomes.
[src:iucn-red-list/biodiversity-p01] This anthropogenic extinction may have started toward the end of the Pleistocene, as some studies suggest that the megafaunal extinction event that took place around the end of the last ice age partly resulted from overhunting.
[src:iucn-red-list/biodiversity-p01] Biologists most often define *biodiversity* as the "totality of genes, species and ecosystems of a region".
[src:iucn-red-list/biodiversity-p01] (2011), there are approximately 8.7 million terrestrial species and 2.2 million oceanic species.
[src:iucn-red-list/biodiversity-p01] The authors note that these estimates are strongest for eukaryotic organisms and likely represent the lower bound of prokaryotic diversity.
[src:iucn-red-list/biodiversity-p01] Since the rate of extinction has increased, many extant species may become extinct before they are described.
[src:iucn-red-list/biodiversity-p01] Not surprisingly, in the Animalia the most studied groups are birds and mammals, whereas fishes and arthropods are the least studied animal groups.
[src:iucn-red-list/biodiversity-p01] During the last century, decreases in biodiversity have been increasingly observed.
[src:iucn-red-list/biodiversity-p01] It was estimated in 2007 that up to 30% of all species will be extinct by 2050.
[src:iucn-red-list/biodiversity-p01] Of these, about one eighth of known plant species are threatened with extinction.
[src:iucn-red-list/biodiversity-p01] Estimates reach as high as 140,000 species per year (based on Species-area theory).
[src:iucn-red-list/biodiversity-p01] This figure indicates unsustainable ecological practices, because few species emerge each year.
[src:iucn-red-list/biodiversity-p01] The rate of species loss is greater now than at any time in human history, with extinctions occurring at rates hundreds of times higher than background extinction rates. and expected to still grow in the upcoming years.
[src:iucn-red-list/biodiversity-p01] As of 2012, some studies suggest that 25% of all mammal species could be extinct in 20 years.
[src:iucn-red-list/biodiversity-p01] According to a 2016 study by the World Wildlife Fund, population abundance among 3,706 monitored vertebrate species is exhibiting a persistent downward trend.
[src:iucn-red-list/biodiversity-p01] The *Living Planet Report 2014* claims that "the number of mammals, birds, reptiles, amphibians, and fish across the globe is, on average, about half the size it was 40 years ago".
[src:iucn-red-list/biodiversity-p01] Of that number, 39% accounts for the terrestrial wildlife gone, 39% for the marine wildlife gone and 76% for the freshwater wildlife gone.
[src:iucn-red-list/biodiversity-p01] Biodiversity took the biggest hit in Latin America, plummeting 83 percent.
[src:iucn-red-list/biodiversity-p01] High-income countries showed a 10% increase in biodiversity, which was canceled out by a loss in low-income countries.
[src:iucn-red-list/biodiversity-p01] This is despite the fact that high-income countries use five times the ecological resources of low-income countries, which was explained as a result of a process whereby wealthy nations are outsourcing resource depletion to poorer nations, which are suffering the greatest ecosystem losses.
[src:iucn-red-list/biodiversity-p01] A 2017 study published in *PLOS One* found that the biomass of insect life in Germany had declined by three-quarters in the last 25 years.
[src:iucn-red-list/biodiversity-p01] Dave Goulson of Sussex University stated that their study suggested that humans "appear to be making vast tracts of land inhospitable to most forms of life, and are currently on course for ecological Armageddon.
[src:iucn-red-list/biodiversity-p01] In 2020 the World Wildlife Fund published a report saying that "biodiversity is being destroyed at a rate unprecedented in human history".
[src:iucn-red-list/biodiversity-p01] The report claims that 68% of the population of the examined species were destroyed in the years 1970 – 2016.
[src:iucn-red-list/biodiversity-p01] Of 70,000 monitored species, around 48% are experiencing population declines from human activity (in 2023), whereas only 3% have increasing populations.
[src:iucn-red-list/biodiversity-p01] Rates of decline in biodiversity in the current sixth mass extinction match or exceed rates of loss in the five previous mass extinction events in the fossil record.
[src:iucn-red-list/biodiversity-p01] Biodiversity loss is in fact "one of the most critical manifestations of the Anthropocene" (since around the 1950s); the continued decline of biodiversity constitutes "an unprecedented threat" to the continued existence of human civilization.
[src:iucn-red-list/biodiversity-p01] The reduction is caused primarily by human impacts, particularly habitat destruction.
[src:iucn-red-list/biodiversity-p01] Since the Stone Age, species loss has accelerated above the average basal rate, driven by human activity.
[src:iucn-red-list/biodiversity-p01] Estimates of species losses are at a rate 100–10,000 times as fast as is typical in the fossil record.
[src:iucn-red-list/biodiversity-p01] Loss of biodiversity results in the loss of natural capital that supplies ecosystem goods and services.
[src:iucn-red-list/biodiversity-p01] Species today are being wiped out at a rate 100 to 1,000 times higher than baseline, and the rate of extinctions is increasing.
[src:iucn-red-list/biodiversity-p01] This process destroys the resilience and adaptability of life on Earth.
[src:iucn-red-list/biodiversity-p01] In 2006, many species were formally classified as rare or endangered or threatened; moreover, scientists have estimated that millions more species are at risk which have not been formally recognized.
[src:iucn-red-list/biodiversity-p01] About 40 percent of the 40,177 species assessed using the IUCN Red List criteria are now listed as threatened with extinction—a total of 16,119.
[src:iucn-red-list/biodiversity-p01] As of late 2022 9251 species were considered part of the IUCN's critically endangered.
[src:iucn-red-list/biodiversity-p01] Numerous scientists and the IPBES *Global Assessment Report on Biodiversity and Ecosystem Services* assert that human population growth and overconsumption are the primary factors in this decline.
[src:iucn-red-list/biodiversity-p01] However, other scientists have criticized this finding and say that loss of habitat caused by "the growth of commodities for export" is the main driver.
[src:iucn-red-list/biodiversity-p01] A 2025 study found that human activities are responsible for biodiversity loss across all species and ecosystems.
[src:iucn-red-list/biodiversity-p01] Climate change is an important driver of global biodiversity loss because of its impacts on ecosystems.
[src:iucn-red-list/biodiversity-p01] At the same time, biodiversity and climate are closely interconnected, as biodiversity influences the mitigation and adaptation potential of ecosystems.
[src:iucn-red-list/biodiversity-p01] For more information on these interactions, see the 'Regulating services' section below.
[src:iucn-red-list/biodiversity-p01] Other studies, however, have pointed out that habitat destruction for the expansion of agriculture and the overexploitation of wildlife are the more significant drivers of contemporary biodiversity loss, not climate change.
[src:iucn-red-list/biodiversity-p01] Biodiversity is not evenly distributed, rather it varies greatly across the globe as well as within regions and seasons.
[src:iucn-red-list/biodiversity-p01] Among other factors, the diversity of all living things (biota) depends on temperature, precipitation, altitude, soils, geography and the interactions between other species.
[src:iucn-red-list/biodiversity-p01] The study of the spatial distribution of organisms, species and ecosystems, is the science of biogeography.
[src:iucn-red-list/biodiversity-p01] Diversity consistently measures higher in the tropics and in other localized regions such as the Cape Floristic Region and lower in polar regions generally.
[src:iucn-red-list/biodiversity-p01] Rain forests that have had wet climates for a long time, such as Yasuní National Park in Ecuador, have particularly high biodiversity.
[src:iucn-red-list/biodiversity-p01] There is local biodiversity, which directly impacts daily life, affecting the availability of fresh water, food choices, and fuel sources for humans.
[src:iucn-red-list/biodiversity-p01] Regional biodiversity includes habitats and ecosystems that synergizes and either overlaps or differs on a regional scale.
[src:iucn-red-list/biodiversity-p01] National biodiversity within a country determines the ability for a country to thrive according to its habitats and ecosystems on a national scale.
[src:iucn-red-list/biodiversity-p01] Also, within a country, endangered species are initially supported on a national level then internationally.
[src:iucn-red-list/biodiversity-p01] Ecotourism may be utilized to support the economy and encourages tourists to continue to visit and support species and ecosystems they visit, while they enjoy the available amenities provided.
[src:iucn-red-list/biodiversity-p01] International biodiversity impacts global livelihood, food systems, and health.
[src:iucn-red-list/biodiversity-p01] Problematic pollution, over consumption, and climate change can devastate international biodiversity.
[src:iucn-red-list/biodiversity-p01] Nature-based solutions are a critical tool for a global resolution.
[src:iucn-red-list/biodiversity-p01] Many species are in danger of becoming extinct and need world leaders to be proactive with the Kunming-Montreal Global Biodiversity Framework.
[src:iucn-red-list/biodiversity-p01] Terrestrial biodiversity is thought to be up to 25 times greater than ocean biodiversity.
[src:iucn-red-list/biodiversity-p01] Forests harbour most of Earth's terrestrial biodiversity.
[src:iucn-red-list/biodiversity-p01] The conservation of the world's biodiversity is thus utterly dependent on the way in which we interact with and use the world's forests.
[src:iucn-red-list/biodiversity-p01] A new method used in 2011, put the total number of species on Earth at 8.7 million, of which 2.1 million were estimated to live in the ocean.
[src:iucn-red-list/biodiversity-p01] However, this estimate seems to under-represent the diversity of microorganisms.
[src:iucn-red-list/biodiversity-p01] Forests provide habitats for 80 percent of amphibian species, 75 percent of bird species and 68 percent of mammal species.
[src:iucn-red-list/biodiversity-p01] About 60 percent of all vascular plants are found in tropical forests.
[src:iucn-red-list/biodiversity-p01] Mangroves provide breeding grounds and nurseries for numerous species of fish and shellfish and help trap sediments that might otherwise adversely affect seagrass beds and coral reefs, which are habitats for many more marine species.
[src:iucn-red-list/biodiversity-p01] Forests span around 4 billion acres (nearly a third of the Earth's land mass) and are home to approximately 80% of the world's biodiversity.
[src:iucn-red-list/biodiversity-p01] About 1 billion hectares are covered by primary forests.
[src:iucn-red-list/biodiversity-p01] Over 700 million hectares of the world's woods are officially protected.
[src:iucn-red-list/biodiversity-p01] The biodiversity of forests varies considerably according to factors such as forest type, geography, climate and soils – in addition to human use.
[src:iucn-red-list/biodiversity-p01] Areas with dense human populations and intense agricultural land use, such as Europe, parts of Bangladesh, China, India and North America, are less intact in terms of their biodiversity.
[src:iucn-red-list/biodiversity-p01] Northern Africa, southern Australia, coastal Brazil, Madagascar and South Africa, are also identified as areas with striking losses in biodiversity intactness.
[src:iucn-red-list/biodiversity-p01] European forests in EU and non-EU nations comprise more than 30% of Europe's land mass (around 227 million hectares), representing an almost 10% growth since 1990.
[src:iucn-red-list/biodiversity-p01] Generally, there is an increase in biodiversity from the poles to the tropics.
[src:iucn-red-list/biodiversity-p01] Thus localities at lower latitudes have more species than localities at higher latitudes.
[src:iucn-red-list/biodiversity-p01] This is often referred to as the latitudinal gradient in species diversity.
[src:iucn-red-list/biodiversity-p01] Several ecological factors may contribute to the gradient, but the ultimate factor behind many of them is the greater mean temperature at the equator compared to that at the poles.
[src:iucn-red-list/biodiversity-p01] Even though terrestrial biodiversity declines from the equator to the poles, some studies claim that this characteristic is unverified in aquatic ecosystems, especially in marine ecosystems.
[src:iucn-red-list/biodiversity-p01] The latitudinal distribution of parasites does not appear to follow this rule.
[src:iucn-red-list/biodiversity-p01] Also, in terrestrial ecosystems the soil bacterial diversity has been shown to be highest in temperate climatic zones, and has been attributed to carbon inputs and habitat connectivity.
[src:iucn-red-list/biodiversity-p01] In 2016, an alternative hypothesis ("the fractal biodiversity") was proposed to explain the biodiversity latitudinal gradient.
[src:iucn-red-list/biodiversity-p01] In this study, the species pool size and the fractal nature of ecosystems were combined to clarify some general patterns of this gradient.
[src:iucn-red-list/biodiversity-p01] This hypothesis considers temperature, moisture, and net primary production (NPP) as the main variables of an ecosystem niche and as the axis of the ecological hypervolume.
[src:iucn-red-list/biodiversity-p01] In this way, it is possible to build fractal hyper volumes, whose fractal dimension rises to three moving towards the equator.
[src:iucn-red-list/biodiversity-p01] A biodiversity hotspot is a region with a high level of endemic species that have experienced great habitat loss.
[src:iucn-red-list/biodiversity-p01] The term hotspot was introduced in 1988 by Norman Myers.
[src:iucn-red-list/biodiversity-p01] While hotspots are spread all over the world, the majority are forest areas and most are located in the tropics.
[src:iucn-red-list/biodiversity-p01] Brazil's Atlantic Forest is considered one such hotspot, containing roughly 20,000 plant species, 1,350 vertebrates and millions of insects, about half of which occur nowhere else.
[src:iucn-red-list/biodiversity-p01] The island of Madagascar and India are also particularly notable.
[src:iucn-red-list/biodiversity-p01] Colombia is characterized by high biodiversity, with the highest rate of species by area unit worldwide and it has the largest number of endemics (species that are not found naturally anywhere else) of any country.
[src:iucn-red-list/biodiversity-p01] About 10% of the species of the Earth can be found in Colombia, including over 1,900 species of bird, more than in Europe and North America combined, Colombia has 10% of the world's mammals species, 14% of the amphibian species and 18% of the bird species of the world.
[src:iucn-red-list/biodiversity-p01] Madagascar dry deciduous forests and lowland rainforests possess a high ratio of endemism.
[src:iucn-red-list/biodiversity-p01] Since the island separated from mainland Africa 66 million years ago, many species and ecosystems have evolved independently.
[src:iucn-red-list/biodiversity-p01] Indonesia's 17,000 islands cover 735,355 square miles (1,904,560 km2) and contain 10% of the world's flowering plants, 12% of mammals and 17% of reptiles, amphibians and birds—along with nearly 240 million people.
[src:iucn-red-list/biodiversity-p01] Many regions of high biodiversity and/or endemism arise from specialized habitats which require unusual adaptations, for example, alpine environments in high mountains, or Northern European peat bogs.
[src:iucn-red-list/biodiversity-p01] Accurately measuring differences in biodiversity can be difficult.
[src:iucn-red-list/biodiversity-p01] Selection bias amongst researchers may contribute to biased empirical research for modern estimates of biodiversity.
[src:iucn-red-list/biodiversity-p01] Biodiversity is the result of 3.5 billion years of evolution.
[src:iucn-red-list/biodiversity-p01] The origin of life has not been established by science, however, some evidence suggests that life may already have been well-established only a few hundred million years after the formation of the Earth.
[src:iucn-red-list/biodiversity-p01] Until approximately 2.5 billion years ago, all life consisted of microorganisms – archaea, bacteria, and single-celled protozoans and protists.
[src:iucn-red-list/biodiversity-p01] Biodiversity grew fast during the Phanerozoic (the last 540 million years), especially during the so-called Cambrian explosion—a period during which nearly every phylum of multicellular organisms first appeared.
[src:iucn-red-list/biodiversity-p01] However, recent studies suggest that this diversification had started earlier, at least in the Ediacaran, and that it continued in the Ordovician.
[src:iucn-red-list/biodiversity-p01] Over the next 400 million years or so, invertebrate diversity showed little overall trend and vertebrate diversity shows an overall exponential trend.
[src:iucn-red-list/biodiversity-p01] This dramatic rise in diversity was marked by periodic, massive losses of diversity classified as mass extinction events.
[src:iucn-red-list/biodiversity-p01] The worst was the Permian-Triassic extinction event, 251 million years ago.
[src:iucn-red-list/biodiversity-p01] Vertebrates took 30 million years to recover from this event.
[src:iucn-red-list/biodiversity-p01] The most recent major mass extinction event, the Cretaceous–Paleogene extinction event, occurred 66 million years ago.
[src:iucn-red-list/biodiversity-p01] This period has attracted more attention than others because it resulted in the extinction of the non-avian dinosaurs, which were represented by many lineages at the end of the Maastrichtian, just before that extinction event.
[src:iucn-red-list/biodiversity-p01] However, many other taxa were affected by this crisis, which affected even marine taxa, such as ammonites, which also became extinct around that time.
[src:iucn-red-list/biodiversity-p01] The biodiversity of the past is called Paleobiodiversity.
[src:iucn-red-list/biodiversity-p01] The fossil record suggests that the last few million years featured the greatest biodiversity in history.
[src:iucn-red-list/biodiversity-p01] However, not all scientists support this view, since there is uncertainty as to how strongly the fossil record is biased by the greater availability and preservation of recent geologic sections.
[src:iucn-red-list/biodiversity-p01] Some scientists believe that corrected for sampling artifacts, modern biodiversity may not be much different from biodiversity 300 million years ago, whereas others consider the fossil record reasonably reflective of the diversification of life.
[src:iucn-red-list/biodiversity-p01] Estimates of the present global macroscopic species diversity vary from 2 million to 100 million, with a best estimate of somewhere near 9 million, the vast majority arthropods.
[src:iucn-red-list/biodiversity-p01] Diversity appears to increase continually in the absence of natural selection.
[src:iucn-red-list/biodiversity-p01] The existence of a *global carrying capacity*, limiting the amount of life that can live at once, is debated, as is the question of whether such a limit would also cap the number of species.
[src:iucn-red-list/biodiversity-p01] While records of life in the sea show a logistic pattern of growth, life on land (insects, plants and tetrapods) shows an exponential rise in diversity.
[src:iucn-red-list/biodiversity-p01] It also appears that the diversity continues to increase over time, especially after mass extinctions.
[src:iucn-red-list/biodiversity-p01] On the other hand, changes through the Phanerozoic correlate much better with the hyperbolic model (widely used in population biology, demography and macrosociology, as well as fossil biodiversity) than with exponential and logistic models.
[src:iucn-red-list/biodiversity-p01] The latter models imply that changes in diversity are guided by a first-order positive feedback (more ancestors, more descendants) and/or a negative feedback arising from resource limitation.
[src:iucn-red-list/biodiversity-p01] Hyperbolic model implies a second-order positive feedback.
[src:iucn-red-list/biodiversity-p01] Differences in the strength of the second-order feedback due to different intensities of interspecific competition might explain the faster rediversification of ammonoids in comparison to bivalves after the end-Permian extinction.
[src:iucn-red-list/biodiversity-p01] The hyperbolic pattern of the world population growth arises from a second-order positive feedback between the population size and the rate of technological growth.
[src:iucn-red-list/biodiversity-p01] The hyperbolic character of biodiversity growth can be similarly accounted for by a feedback between diversity and community structure complexity.
[src:iucn-red-list/biodiversity-p01] The similarity between the curves of biodiversity and human population probably comes from the fact that both are derived from the interference of the hyperbolic trend with cyclical and stochastic dynamics.
[src:iucn-red-list/biodiversity-p01] Most biologists agree however that the period since human emergence is part of a new mass extinction, named the Holocene extinction event, caused primarily by the impact humans are having on the environment.
[src:iucn-red-list/biodiversity-p01] It has been argued that the present rate of extinction is sufficient to eliminate most species on the planet Earth within 100 years.
[src:iucn-red-list/biodiversity-p01] New species are regularly discovered (on average between 5–10,000 new species each year, most of them insects) and many, though discovered, are not yet classified (estimates are that nearly 90% of all arthropods are not yet classified).
[src:iucn-red-list/biodiversity-p01] Most of the terrestrial diversity is found in tropical forests and in general, the land has more species than the ocean; some 8.7 million species may exist on Earth, of which some 2.1 million live in the ocean.
[src:iucn-red-list/biodiversity-p01] It is estimated that 5 to 50 billion species have existed on the planet.
[src:iucn-red-list/biodiversity-p01] Assuming that there may be a maximum of about 50 million species currently alive, it stands to reason that greater than 99% of the planet's species went extinct prior to the evolution of humans.
[src:iucn-red-list/biodiversity-p01] Estimates on the number of Earth's current species range from 10 million to 14 million, of which about 1.2 million have been documented and over 86% have not yet been described.
[src:iucn-red-list/biodiversity-p01] However, a May 2016 scientific report estimates that 1 trillion species are currently on Earth, with only one-thousandth of one percent described.
[src:iucn-red-list/biodiversity-p01] The total amount of related DNA base pairs on Earth is estimated at 5.0 × 1037 and weighs 50 billion tonnes.
[src:iucn-red-list/biodiversity-p01] In comparison, the total mass of the biosphere has been estimated to be as much as four trillion tons of carbon.
[src:iucn-red-list/biodiversity-p01] In July 2016, scientists reported identifying a set of 355 genes from the last universal common ancestor (LUCA) of all organisms living on Earth.
[src:iucn-red-list/biodiversity-p01] The age of Earth is about 4.54 billion years.
[src:iucn-red-list/biodiversity-p01] The earliest undisputed evidence of life dates at least from 3.7 billion years ago, during the Eoarchean era after a geological crust started to solidify following the earlier molten Hadean eon.
[src:iucn-red-list/biodiversity-p01] There are microbial mat fossils found in 3.48 billion-year-old sandstone discovered in Western Australia.
[src:iucn-red-list/biodiversity-p01] Other early physical evidence of a biogenic substance is graphite in 3.7 billion-year-old meta-sedimentary rocks discovered in Western Greenland.
[src:iucn-red-list/biodiversity-p01] More recently, in 2015, "remains of biotic life" were found in 4.1 billion-year-old rocks in Western Australia.
[src:iucn-red-list/biodiversity-p01] There have been many claims about biodiversity's effect on the ecosystem services, especially *provisioning* and *regulating services*.
[src:iucn-red-list/biodiversity-p01] Some of those claims have been validated, some are incorrect and some lack enough evidence to draw definitive conclusions.
[src:iucn-red-list/biodiversity-p01] Experiments with controlled environments have shown that humans cannot easily build ecosystems to support human needs; for example insect pollination cannot be mimicked, though there have been attempts to create artificial pollinators using unmanned aerial vehicles.
[src:iucn-red-list/biodiversity-p01] The economic activity of pollination alone represented between $2.1–14.6 billion in 2003.
[src:iucn-red-list/biodiversity-p01] Other sources have reported somewhat conflicting results and in 1997 Robert Costanza and his colleagues reported the estimated global value of ecosystem services (not captured in traditional markets) at an average of $33 trillion annually.
[src:iucn-red-list/biodiversity-p01] Biodiversity plays a role in multiple ecological regulating services that strengthen the stability, functioning and adaptability of ecosystems.
[src:iucn-red-list/biodiversity-p01] For example, plant species richness can increase functional diversity in many ecosystems.
[src:iucn-red-list/biodiversity-p01] Different plant organisms living together can perform complementary roles such as nutrient cycling and water regulation, which can contribute to the stabilisation of ecosystem processes under climate stress, a mechanism known as niche complementarity.
[src:iucn-red-list/biodiversity-p01] This could include enhanced transpiration and soil moisture regulation, as more efficient water use can be promoted by the variety of different leaf traits and root depths, which in turn can reduce drought stress and mitigate heat impact.
[src:iucn-red-list/biodiversity-p01] Climate change is also associated with higher pathogen pressure on terrestrial and marine ecosystems.
[src:iucn-red-list/biodiversity-p01] In many ecosystems higher biodiversity could contribute to greater resilience to pests and diseases, as diversity in host traits and interactions can interrupt disease spread and reduce the severity of the outbreak.
[src:iucn-red-list/biodiversity-p01] In coastal ecosystems genetic diversity within a species can further enhance its adaptive capacity by providing a range of traits that support populations to persist under changing temperature and precipitation regimes.
[src:iucn-red-list/biodiversity-p01] Furthermore, in terrestrial ecosystems higher biodiversity can promote mutualistic interactions (like pollination or mycorrhizal networks), which can enhance nutrient uptake and support overall productivity and resilience.
[src:iucn-red-list/biodiversity-p01] The other category of agricultural diversity is called interspecific diversity and refers to the number and types of different species.
[src:iucn-red-list/biodiversity-p01] Agricultural diversity can also be divided by whether it is 'planned' diversity or 'associated' diversity.
[src:iucn-red-list/biodiversity-p01] This is a functional classification that we impose and not an intrinsic feature of life or diversity.
[src:iucn-red-list/biodiversity-p01] Associated biodiversity can be damaging or beneficial.
[src:iucn-red-list/biodiversity-p01] The beneficial associated biodiversity include for instance wild pollinators such as wild bees and syrphid flies that pollinate crops and natural enemies and antagonists to pests and pathogens.
[src:iucn-red-list/biodiversity-p01] Beneficial associated biodiversity occurs abundantly in crop fields and provide multiple ecosystem services such as pest control, nutrient cycling and pollination that support crop production.
[src:iucn-red-list/biodiversity-p01] Although about 80 percent of humans' food supply comes from just 20 kinds of plants, humans use at least 40,000 species.
[src:iucn-red-list/biodiversity-p01] Earth's surviving biodiversity provides resources for increasing the range of food and other products suitable for human use, although the present extinction rate shrinks that potential.
[src:iucn-red-list/biodiversity-p01] Biodiversity's relevance to human health is becoming an international political issue, as scientific evidence builds on the global health implications of biodiversity loss.
[src:iucn-red-list/biodiversity-p01] Some of the health issues influenced by biodiversity include dietary health and nutrition security, infectious disease, medical science and medicinal resources, social and psychological health.
[src:iucn-red-list/biodiversity-p01] Biodiversity is also known to have an important role in reducing disaster risk, including rising sea levels.
[src:iucn-red-list/biodiversity-p01] For example, wetland ecosystems along coastal communities serve as excellent water filtration systems, storage, and ultimately create a buffer region between the ocean and mainland neighborhoods in order to prevent water reaching these communities under climate change pressures or storm surges.
[src:iucn-red-list/biodiversity-p01] Other examples of diverse species or organisms are present around the world, offering their resourceful utilities to provide protection of human survival.
[src:iucn-red-list/biodiversity-p01] Biodiversity provides critical support for drug discovery and the availability of medicinal resources.
[src:iucn-red-list/biodiversity-p01] Only a tiny fraction of wild species has been investigated for medical potential.
[src:iucn-red-list/biodiversity-p01] This process of bioprospecting can increase biodiversity loss, as well as violating the laws of the communities and states from which the resources are taken.
[src:iucn-red-list/biodiversity-p01] According to the Boston Consulting Group, in 2021, the economic value that biodiversity has on society comes down to four definable terms: regulation, culture, habitat, and provisioning.
[src:iucn-red-list/biodiversity-p01] To sum these up in a relatively short manner, biodiversity helps maintain habitat and animal functions that provide considerable amounts of resources that benefit the economy.
[src:iucn-red-list/biodiversity-p01] Biodiversity's economic resources are worth at around $150 trillion annually which is roughly twice the world's GDP.
[src:iucn-red-list/biodiversity-p01] The loss of biodiversity is actually harming the GDP of the world by costing an estimated $5 trillion annually.
[src:iucn-red-list/biodiversity-p01] Business supply chains rely heavily on ecosystems remaining relatively maintained and nurtured.
[src:iucn-red-list/biodiversity-p01] A disruption to these supply chains would negatively impact many businesses that would end up costing them more than what they are gaining.
[src:iucn-red-list/biodiversity-p01] Philosophically it could be argued that biodiversity has intrinsic aesthetic and spiritual value to mankind *in and of itself*.
[src:iucn-red-list/biodiversity-p01] This idea can be used as a counterweight to the notion that tropical forests and other ecological realms are only worthy of conservation because of the services they provide.
[src:iucn-red-list/biodiversity-p01] Biodiversity also affords many non-material benefits including spiritual and aesthetic values, knowledge systems and education.
[src:iucn-red-list/biodiversity-p01] A variety of objective means exist to empirically measure biodiversity.
[src:iucn-red-list/biodiversity-p01] Each measure relates to a particular use of the data, and is likely to be associated with the variety of genes.
[src:iucn-red-list/biodiversity-p01] Biodiversity is commonly measured in terms of taxonomic richness of a geographic area over a time interval.
[src:iucn-red-list/biodiversity-p01] In order to calculate biodiversity, species evenness, species richness, and species diversity are to be obtained first.
[src:iucn-red-list/biodiversity-p01] *Species evenness* is the relative number of individuals of each species in a given area.
[src:iucn-red-list/biodiversity-p01] *Species richness* is the number of species present in a given area.
[src:iucn-red-list/biodiversity-p01] *Species diversity* is the relationship between species evenness and species richness.
[src:iucn-red-list/biodiversity-p01] There are many ways to measure biodiversity within a given ecosystem.
[src:iucn-red-list/biodiversity-p01] However, the two most popular are Shannon-Weaver diversity index, commonly referred to as Shannon diversity index, and the other is Simpsons diversity index.
[src:iucn-red-list/biodiversity-p01] Although many scientists prefer to use Shannon's diversity index simply because it takes into account species richness.
[src:iucn-red-list/biodiversity-p01] Less than 1% of all species that have been described have been studied beyond noting their existence.
[src:iucn-red-list/biodiversity-p01] The vast majority of Earth's species are microbial.
[src:iucn-red-list/biodiversity-p01] Contemporary biodiversity physics is "firmly fixated on the visible [macroscopic] world".
[src:iucn-red-list/biodiversity-p01] For example, microbial life is metabolically and environmentally more diverse than multicellular life (see e.g., extremophile).
[src:iucn-red-list/biodiversity-p01] "On the tree of life, based on analyses of small-subunit ribosomal RNA, visible life consists of barely noticeable twigs.
[src:iucn-red-list/biodiversity-p01] The inverse relationship of size and population recurs higher on the evolutionary ladder—to a first approximation, all multicellular species on Earth are insects".
[src:iucn-red-list/biodiversity-p01] Insect extinction rates are high—supporting the Holocene extinction hypothesis.
[src:iucn-red-list/biodiversity-p01] Biodiversity naturally varies due to seasonal shifts.
[src:iucn-red-list/biodiversity-p01] Spring's arrival enhances biodiversity as numerous species breed and feed, while winter's onset temporarily reduces it as some insects perish and migrating animals leave.
[src:iucn-red-list/biodiversity-p01] Additionally, the seasonal fluctuation in plant and invertebrate populations influences biodiversity.
[src:iucn-red-list/biodiversity-p01] Barriers such as large rivers, seas, oceans, mountains and deserts encourage diversity by enabling independent evolution on either side of the barrier, via the process of allopatric speciation.
[src:iucn-red-list/biodiversity-p01] The term invasive species is applied to species that breach the natural barriers that would normally keep them constrained.
[src:iucn-red-list/biodiversity-p01] Without barriers, such species occupy new territory, often supplanting native species by occupying their niches, or by using resources that would normally sustain native species.
[src:iucn-red-list/biodiversity-p01] Species are increasingly being moved by humans (on purpose and accidentally).
[src:iucn-red-list/biodiversity-p01] Some studies say that diverse ecosystems are more resilient and resist invasive plants and animals.
[src:iucn-red-list/biodiversity-p01] Many studies cite effects of invasive species on natives, but not extinctions.
[src:iucn-red-list/biodiversity-p01] Invasive species seem to increase local (alpha diversity) diversity, which decreases turnover of diversity (beta diversity).
[src:iucn-red-list/biodiversity-p01] Overall gamma diversity may be lowered because species are going extinct because of other causes, but even some of the most insidious invaders (e.g.: Dutch elm disease, emerald ash borer, chestnut blight in North America) have not caused their host species to become extinct.
[src:iucn-red-list/biodiversity-p01] Extirpation, population decline and homogenization of regional biodiversity are much more common.
[src:iucn-red-list/biodiversity-p01] Human activities have frequently been the cause of invasive species circumventing their barriers, by introducing them for food and other purposes.
[src:iucn-red-list/biodiversity-p01] Human activities therefore allow species to migrate to new areas (and thus become invasive) occurred on time scales much shorter than historically have been required for a species to extend its range.
[src:iucn-red-list/biodiversity-p01] At present, several countries have already imported so many exotic species, particularly agricultural and ornamental plants, that their indigenous fauna/flora may be outnumbered.
[src:iucn-red-list/biodiversity-p01] For example, the introduction of kudzu from Southeast Asia to Canada and the United States has threatened biodiversity in certain areas.
[src:iucn-red-list/biodiversity-p01] Another example are pines, which have invaded forests, shrublands and grasslands in the southern hemisphere.
[src:iucn-red-list/biodiversity-p01] Endemic species can be threatened with extinction through the process of genetic pollution, i.e. uncontrolled hybridization, introgression and genetic swamping.
[src:iucn-red-list/biodiversity-p01] Genetic pollution leads to homogenization or replacement of local genomes as a result of either a numerical and/or fitness advantage of an introduced species.
[src:iucn-red-list/biodiversity-p01] Hybridization and introgression are side-effects of introduction and invasion.
[src:iucn-red-list/biodiversity-p01] These phenomena can be especially detrimental to rare species that come into contact with more abundant ones.
[src:iucn-red-list/biodiversity-p01] The abundant species can interbreed with the rare species, swamping its gene pool.
[src:iucn-red-list/biodiversity-p01] This problem is not always apparent from morphological (outward appearance) observations alone.
[src:iucn-red-list/biodiversity-p01] Some degree of gene flow is normal adaptation and not all gene and genotype constellations can be preserved.
[src:iucn-red-list/biodiversity-p01] However, hybridization with or without introgression may, nevertheless, threaten a rare species' existence.
[src:iucn-red-list/biodiversity-p01] Conservation biology matured in the mid-20th century as ecologists, naturalists and other scientists began to research and address issues pertaining to global biodiversity declines.
[src:iucn-red-list/biodiversity-p01] The conservation ethic advocates management of natural resources for the purpose of sustaining biodiversity in species, ecosystems, the evolutionary process and human culture and society.
[src:iucn-red-list/biodiversity-p01] Conservation biology is reforming around strategic plans to protect biodiversity.
[src:iucn-red-list/biodiversity-p01] Preserving global biodiversity is a priority in strategic conservation plans that are designed to engage public policy and concerns affecting local, regional and global scales of communities, ecosystems and cultures.
[src:iucn-red-list/biodiversity-p01] Action plans identify ways of sustaining human well-being, employing natural capital, macroeconomic policies including economic incentives, and ecosystem services.
[src:iucn-red-list/biodiversity-p01] In the EU Directive 1999/22/EC zoos are described as having a role in the preservation of the biodiversity of wildlife animals by conducting research or participation in breeding programs.
[src:iucn-red-list/biodiversity-p01] Removal of exotic species will allow the species that they have negatively impacted to recover their ecological niches.
[src:iucn-red-list/biodiversity-p01] Exotic species that have become pests can be identified taxonomically (e.g., with Digital Automated Identification SYstem (DAISY), using the barcode of life).
[src:iucn-red-list/biodiversity-p01] Removal is practical only given large groups of individuals due to the economic cost.
[src:iucn-red-list/biodiversity-p01] As sustainable populations of the remaining native species in an area become assured, "missing" species that are candidates for reintroduction can be identified using databases such as the *Encyclopedia of Life* and the Global Biodiversity Information Facility.
[src:iucn-red-list/biodiversity-p02] Protected areas, including forest reserves and biosphere reserves, serve many functions including for affording protection to wild animals and their habitat.
[src:iucn-red-list/biodiversity-p02] Protected areas have been set up all over the world with the specific aim of protecting and conserving plants and animals.
[src:iucn-red-list/biodiversity-p02] Some scientists have called on the global community to designate as protected areas of 30 percent of the planet by 2030, and 50 percent by 2050, in order to mitigate biodiversity loss from anthropogenic causes.
[src:iucn-red-list/biodiversity-p02] The target of protecting 30% of the area of the planet by the year 2030 (30 by 30) was adopted by almost 200 countries in the 2022 United Nations Biodiversity Conference.
[src:iucn-red-list/biodiversity-p02] At the moment of adoption (December 2022) 17% of land territory and 10% of ocean territory were protected.
[src:iucn-red-list/biodiversity-p02] In a study published 4 September 2020 in Science Advances researchers mapped out regions that can help meet critical conservation and climate goals.
[src:iucn-red-list/biodiversity-p02] Protected areas safeguard nature and cultural resources and contribute to livelihoods, particularly at local level.
[src:iucn-red-list/biodiversity-p02] There are over 238 563 designated protected areas worldwide, equivalent to 14.9 percent of the earth's land surface, varying in their extension, level of protection, and type of management (IUCN, 2018).
[src:iucn-red-list/biodiversity-p02] The benefits of protected areas extend beyond their immediate environment and time.
[src:iucn-red-list/biodiversity-p02] In addition to conserving nature, protected areas are crucial for securing the long-term delivery of ecosystem services.
[src:iucn-red-list/biodiversity-p02] They provide numerous benefits including the conservation of genetic resources for food and agriculture, the provision of medicine and health benefits, the provision of water, recreation and tourism, and for acting as a buffer against disaster.
[src:iucn-red-list/biodiversity-p02] Increasingly, there is acknowledgement of the wider socioeconomic values of these natural ecosystems and of the ecosystem services they can provide.
[src:iucn-red-list/biodiversity-p02] A national park is a large natural or near natural area set aside to protect large-scale ecological processes, which also provide a foundation for environmentally and culturally compatible, spiritual, scientific, educational, recreational and visitor opportunities.
[src:iucn-red-list/biodiversity-p02] These areas are selected by governments or private organizations to protect natural biodiversity along with its underlying ecological structure and supporting environmental processes, and to promote education and recreation.
[src:iucn-red-list/biodiversity-p02] The International Union for Conservation of Nature (IUCN), and its World Commission on Protected Areas (WCPA), has defined "National Park" as its Category II type of protected areas.
[src:iucn-red-list/biodiversity-p02] Wildlife sanctuaries are areas of either shelter for animals who are unable to live in the wild on their own, or they are temporary rehabilitation centers for wildlife to improve in their overall health and wellbeing.
[src:iucn-red-list/biodiversity-p02] Both of these serve as places in which biodiversity can be preserved rather than harmed.
[src:iucn-red-list/biodiversity-p02] According to an article published in the National Park Service website, national parks aim their resources at maintaining animal and habitat integrity through conservation and preservation of their ecosystems.
[src:iucn-red-list/biodiversity-p02] This along with educating the general public on wildlife functions, the aim for an increase in biodiversity is one of many goals trying to be focused on through national parks.
[src:iucn-red-list/biodiversity-p02] Forest protected areas are a subset of all protected areas in which a significant portion of the area is forest.
[src:iucn-red-list/biodiversity-p02] This may be the whole or only a part of the protected area.
[src:iucn-red-list/biodiversity-p02] Globally, 18 percent of the world's forest area, or more than 700 million hectares, fall within legally established protected areas such as national parks, conservation areas and game reserves.
[src:iucn-red-list/biodiversity-p02] There is an estimated 726 million ha of forest in protected areas worldwide.
[src:iucn-red-list/biodiversity-p02] Of the six major world regions, South America has the highest share of forests in protected areas, 31 percent.
[src:iucn-red-list/biodiversity-p02] The forests play a vital role in harboring more than 45,000 floral and 81,000 faunal species of which 5150 floral and 1837 faunal species are endemic.
[src:iucn-red-list/biodiversity-p02] In addition, there are 60,065 different tree species in the world.
[src:iucn-red-list/biodiversity-p02] Plant and animal species confined to a specific geographical area are called endemic species.
[src:iucn-red-list/biodiversity-p02] In forest reserves, rights to activities like hunting and grazing are sometimes given to communities living on the fringes of the forest, who sustain their livelihood partially or wholly from forest resources or products.
[src:iucn-red-list/biodiversity-p02] Approximately 50 million hectares (or 24%) of European forest land is protected for biodiversity and landscape protection.
[src:iucn-red-list/biodiversity-p02] Forests allocated for soil, water, and other ecosystem services encompass around 72 million hectares (32% of European forest area).
[src:iucn-red-list/biodiversity-p02] It stated that "the state of nature has deteriorated at an unprecedented and accelerating rate".
[src:iucn-red-list/biodiversity-p02] To fix the problem, humanity will need a transformative change, including sustainable agriculture, reductions in consumption and waste, fishing quotas and collaborative water management.
[src:iucn-red-list/biodiversity-p02] The concept of nature-positive is playing a role in mainstreaming the goals of the Global Biodiversity Framework (GBF) for biodiversity.
[src:iucn-red-list/biodiversity-p02] The aim of mainstreaming is to embed biodiversity considerations into public and private practice to conserve and sustainably use biodiversity on global and local levels.
[src:iucn-red-list/biodiversity-p02] The concept of nature-positive refers to the societal goal to halt and reverse biodiversity loss, measured from a baseline of 2020 levels, and to achieve full so-called "nature recovery" by 2050.
[src:iucn-red-list/biodiversity-p02] Citizen science, also known as public participation in scientific research, has been widely used in environmental sciences and is particularly popular in a biodiversity-related context.
[src:iucn-red-list/biodiversity-p02] It has been used to enable scientists to involve the general public in biodiversity research, thereby enabling the scientists to collect data that they would otherwise not have been able to obtain.
[src:iucn-red-list/biodiversity-p02] Volunteer observers have made significant contributions to on-the-ground knowledge about biodiversity, and recent improvements in technology have helped increase the flow and quality of occurrences from citizen sources.
[src:iucn-red-list/biodiversity-p02] A 2016 study published in Biological Conservation registers the massive contributions that citizen scientists already make to data mediated by the Global Biodiversity Information Facility (GBIF).
[src:iucn-red-list/biodiversity-p02] Despite some limitations of the dataset-level analysis, it is clear that nearly half of all occurrence records shared through the GBIF network come from datasets with significant volunteer contributions.
[src:iucn-red-list/biodiversity-p02] Recording and sharing observations are enabled by several global-scale platforms, including iNaturalist and eBird.
[src:iucn-red-list/biodiversity-p02] Global agreements such as the Convention on Biological Diversity, give "sovereign national rights over biological resources" (not property).
[src:iucn-red-list/biodiversity-p02] The agreements commit countries to "conserve biodiversity", "develop resources for sustainability" and "share the benefits" resulting from their use.
[src:iucn-red-list/biodiversity-p02] Biodiverse countries that allow bioprospecting or collection of natural products, expect a share of the benefits rather than allowing the individual or institution that discovers/exploits the resource to capture them privately.
[src:iucn-red-list/biodiversity-p02] Bioprospecting can become a type of biopiracy when such principles are not respected.
[src:iucn-red-list/biodiversity-p02] Sovereignty principles can rely upon what is better known as Access and Benefit Sharing Agreements (ABAs).
[src:iucn-red-list/biodiversity-p02] The Convention on Biodiversity implies informed consent between the source country and the collector, to establish which resource will be used and for what and to settle on a fair agreement on benefit sharing.
[src:iucn-red-list/biodiversity-p02] The agreement includes also recovering 30% of earth degraded ecosystems and increasing funding for biodiversity issues.
[src:iucn-red-list/biodiversity-p02] In May 2020, the European Union published its Biodiversity Strategy for 2030.
[src:iucn-red-list/biodiversity-p02] The biodiversity strategy is an essential part of the climate change mitigation strategy of the European Union.
[src:iucn-red-list/biodiversity-p02] From the 25% of the European budget that will go to fight climate change, large part will go to restore biodiversity and nature based solutions.
[src:iucn-red-list/biodiversity-p02] Approximately half of the global GDP depend on nature.
[src:iucn-red-list/biodiversity-p02] In Europe many parts of the economy that generate trillions of euros per year depend on nature.
[src:iucn-red-list/biodiversity-p02] The benefits of Natura 2000 alone in Europe are €200 – €300 billion per year.
[src:iucn-red-list/biodiversity-p02] Uniform approval for use of biodiversity as a legal standard has not been achieved, however.
[src:iucn-red-list/biodiversity-p02] Bosselman argues that biodiversity should not be used as a legal standard, claiming that the remaining areas of scientific uncertainty cause unacceptable administrative waste and increase litigation without promoting preservation goals.
[src:iucn-red-list/biodiversity-p02] India passed the Biological Diversity Act in 2002 for the conservation of biological diversity in India.
[src:iucn-red-list/biodiversity-p02] The Act also provides mechanisms for equitable sharing of benefits from the use of traditional biological resources and knowledge.
[src:iucn-red-list/biological-species] A **species** (pl. species) is the basic unit of classification and a taxonomic rank of an organism, as well as a unit of biodiversity.
[src:iucn-red-list/biological-species] It can be defined as the largest group of organisms in which any two individuals of the appropriate sexes or mating types can produce fertile offspring, typically by sexual reproduction.
[src:iucn-red-list/biological-species] Other ways of defining species include their karyotype, DNA sequence, morphology, behaviour, or ecological niche.
[src:iucn-red-list/biological-species] In addition, palaeontologists use the concept of the chronospecies since fossil reproduction cannot be examined.
[src:iucn-red-list/biological-species] The most recent rigorous estimate for the total number of species of eukaryotes is between 8 and 8.7 million.
[src:iucn-red-list/biological-species] About 14% of these had been described by 2011.
[src:iucn-red-list/biological-species] All species (except viruses) are given a two-part name, a "binomen".
[src:iucn-red-list/biological-species] The first part of a binomen is the name of a genus to which the species belongs.
[src:iucn-red-list/biological-species] The second part is called the specific name or the specific epithet (in botanical nomenclature, also sometimes in zoological nomenclature).
[src:iucn-red-list/biological-species] For example, *Boa constrictor* is one of the species of the genus *Boa*, with *constrictor* being the specific name.
[src:iucn-red-list/biological-species] While the definitions given above may seem adequate at first glance, when looked at more closely they represent problematic species concepts.
[src:iucn-red-list/biological-species] For example, the boundaries between closely related species become unclear with hybridisation, in a species complex of hundreds of similar microspecies, and in a ring species.
[src:iucn-red-list/biological-species] Also, among organisms that reproduce only asexually, the concept of a reproductive species breaks down, and each clonal lineage is potentially a microspecies.
[src:iucn-red-list/biological-species] Although none of these are entirely satisfactory definitions, and while the concept of species may not be a perfect model of life, it is still a useful tool to scientists and conservationists for studying life on Earth, regardless of the theoretical difficulties.
[src:iucn-red-list/biological-species] If species were fixed and distinct from one another, there would be no problem, but evolutionary processes cause species to change.
[src:iucn-red-list/biological-species] This obliges taxonomists to decide, for example, when enough change has occurred to declare that a fossil lineage should be divided into multiple chronospecies, or when populations have diverged to have enough distinct character states to be described as cladistic species.
[src:iucn-red-list/biological-species] Species and higher taxa were seen from Aristotle until the 18th century as categories that could be arranged in a hierarchy, the great chain of being.
[src:iucn-red-list/biological-species] In the 19th century, biologists grasped that species could evolve given sufficient time.
[src:iucn-red-list/biological-species] Charles Darwin's 1859 book *On the Origin of Species* explained how species could arise by natural selection.
[src:iucn-red-list/biological-species] That understanding was greatly extended in the 20th century through genetics and population ecology.
[src:iucn-red-list/biological-species] Genetic variability arises from mutations and recombination, while organisms are mobile, leading to geographical isolation and genetic drift with varying selection pressures.
[src:iucn-red-list/biological-species] Genes can sometimes be exchanged between species by horizontal gene transfer; new species can arise rapidly through hybridisation and polyploidy; and species may become extinct for a variety of reasons, With several mass extinction events occurring throughout history.
[src:iucn-red-list/biological-species] Viruses are a special case, driven by a balance of mutation and selection, and can be treated as quasispecies.
[src:iucn-red-list/biological-species] Biologists and taxonomists have made many attempts to define species, beginning from morphology and moving towards genetics.
[src:iucn-red-list/biological-species] Early taxonomists such as Linnaeus had no option but to describe what they saw: this was later formalised as the typological or morphological species concept.
[src:iucn-red-list/biological-species] Ernst Mayr emphasised reproductive isolation, but this, like other species concepts, can be hard or even impossible to test for groups of organisms separated in space or time.
[src:iucn-red-list/biological-species] Later biologists have tried to refine Mayr's definition with the recognition and cohesion concepts, among others.
[src:iucn-red-list/biological-species] Many of the concepts are quite similar or overlap, so they are not easy to count: the biologist R.
[src:iucn-red-list/biological-species] Mayden recorded about 24 concepts, and the philosopher of science John Wilkins counted 26.
[src:iucn-red-list/biological-species] A typological species is a group of organisms in which individuals conform to certain fixed properties (a type, which may be defined by a chosen 'nominal species'), so that even pre-literate people often recognise the same taxon as do modern taxonomists.
[src:iucn-red-list/biological-species] Modern-day field guides and identification websites such as iNaturalist use this concept.
[src:iucn-red-list/biological-species] The clusters of variations or phenotypes within specimens (such as longer or shorter tails) would differentiate the species.
[src:iucn-red-list/biological-species] This method was used as a "classical" method of determining species, such as with Linnaeus, early in evolutionary theory.
[src:iucn-red-list/biological-species] However, different phenotypes are not necessarily different species (e.g. a four-winged *Drosophila* born to a two-winged mother is not a different species).
[src:iucn-red-list/biological-species] Species named in this manner are called *morphospecies*.
[src:iucn-red-list/biological-species] Crovello and Peter Sneath proposed a variation on the morphological species concept, a phenetic species, defined as a set of organisms with a similar phenotype to each other, but a different phenotype from other sets of organisms.
[src:iucn-red-list/biological-species] It differs from the morphological species concept in including a numerical measure of distance or similarity to cluster entities based on multivariate comparisons of a reasonably large number of phenotypic traits.
[src:iucn-red-list/biological-species] A mate-recognition species is a group of sexually reproducing organisms that recognise one another as potential mates.
[src:iucn-red-list/biological-species] A further development of the recognition concept is provided by the biosemiotic concept of species.
[src:iucn-red-list/biological-species] In microbiology, genes can move freely even between distantly related bacteria, possibly extending to the whole bacterial domain.
[src:iucn-red-list/biological-species] As a rule of thumb, microbiologists had assumed that members of Bacteria or Archaea with 16S ribosomal RNA gene sequences more similar than 97% to each other need to be checked by DNA–DNA hybridisation to decide if they belong to the same species.
[src:iucn-red-list/biological-species] This concept was narrowed in 2006 to a similarity of 98.7%.
[src:iucn-red-list/biological-species] The 16S sequence is an example of a single locus which is simple enough for non-specialists to apply and, in most cases, sufficient to distinguish species.
[src:iucn-red-list/biological-species] Using a single easy-to-use locus to distinguish taxa is called DNA barcoding.
[src:iucn-red-list/biological-species] One of the barcodes for eukaryotes is a region of mitochondrial DNA within the gene for cytochrome c oxidase.
[src:iucn-red-list/biological-species] A database, Barcode of Life Data System, contains DNA barcode sequences from over 190,000 species.
[src:iucn-red-list/biological-species] However, scientists such as Rob DeSalle have expressed concern that classical taxonomy and DNA barcoding, which they consider a misnomer, need to be reconciled, as they delimit species differently.
[src:iucn-red-list/biological-species] Genetic introgression mediated by endosymbionts and other vectors can further make barcodes ineffective in the identification of species.
[src:iucn-red-list/biological-species] A singular locus can be a good proxy of time of divergence assuming the chosen locus evolved like most of the rest of the genome.
[src:iucn-red-list/biological-species] This assumption can be broken by horizontal gene transfer affecting the locus itself.
[src:iucn-red-list/biological-species] Rapid modes of evolution separating biological species (speciation) over a short timespan would also decouple the species concept from time itself.
[src:iucn-red-list/biological-species] Among bacteria, there are several cases where very different genomes share 99.9% 16S identity.
[src:iucn-red-list/biological-species] Using multiple (usually fewer than 10) loci for comparison provides more phylogenetic signal compared to comparing versions of the same loci as more mutations can be captured.
[src:iucn-red-list/biological-species] As a result, it provides improved taxonomic resolution compared to single-locus comparison, giving results more similar to the expensive "gold standard" of whole genome comparison at a small increase in cost.
[src:iucn-red-list/biological-species] Even when whole genomes are available, there are good reasons to only compare select genes: many genes are not universally found in all genomes, so they provide limited taxonomic signal while still adding to the computational cost of comparison.
[src:iucn-red-list/biological-species] In situations like this, tens to hundreds of loci may be extracted from each genome and used together.
[src:iucn-red-list/biological-species] As with comparisons with fewer loci, marker genes used for this purpose should be genes with low rates of horizontal transfer and gene duplication, few known instances of horizontal transfer, and high occurrence in the sampled genomes.
[src:iucn-red-list/biological-species] With prokaryotes, marker genes can be used to delimit taxa down to the genus level, with whole-genome comparison reserved to separate species from each other.
[src:iucn-red-list/biological-species] The surefire way to capture all gene flow among populations is to compare their entire genomes.
[src:iucn-red-list/biological-species] The average nucleotide identity (ANI) method quantifies genetic distance between entire genomes, using regions of about 10,000 base pairs.
[src:iucn-red-list/biological-species] With enough data from genomes of one genus, algorithms can be used to categorize species, as for *Pseudomonas avellanae* in 2013, and for all sequenced bacteria and archaea since 2020.
[src:iucn-red-list/biological-species] Observed ANI values among prokaryotic sequences appear to have an "ANI gap" at 85–95%, suggesting that a genetic boundary suitable for defining a species concept is present.
[src:iucn-red-list/biological-species] A phylogenetic or cladistic species is "the smallest aggregation of populations (sexual) or lineages (asexual) diagnosable by a unique combination of character states in comparable individuals (semaphoronts)".
[src:iucn-red-list/biological-species] The empirical basis – observed character states – provides the evidence to support hypotheses about evolutionarily divergent lineages that have maintained their hereditary integrity through time and space.
[src:iucn-red-list/biological-species] Molecular markers may be used to determine diagnostic genetic differences in the nuclear or mitochondrial DNA of various species.
[src:iucn-red-list/biological-species] For example, in a study done on fungi, studying the nucleotide characters using cladistic species produced the most accurate results in recognising the numerous fungi species of all the concepts studied.
[src:iucn-red-list/biological-species] Others have called this approach taxonomic inflation, diluting the species concept and making taxonomy unstable.
[src:iucn-red-list/biological-species] Unlike the biological species concept, a cladistic species does not rely on reproductive isolation – its criteria are independent of processes that are integral in other concepts.
[src:iucn-red-list/biological-species] Therefore, it applies to asexual lineages.
[src:iucn-red-list/biological-species] However, it does not always provide clear cut and intuitively satisfying boundaries between taxa, and may require multiple sources of evidence, such as more than one polymorphic locus, to give plausible results.
[src:iucn-red-list/biological-species] An evolutionary species, suggested by George Gaylord Simpson in 1951, is "an entity composed of organisms which maintains its identity from other such entities through time and over space, and which has its own independent evolutionary fate and historical tendencies".
[src:iucn-red-list/biological-species] This differs from the biological species concept in embodying persistence over time.
[src:iucn-red-list/biological-species] They further suggested that the concept works for both asexual and sexually-reproducing species.
[src:iucn-red-list/biological-species] A version of the concept is Kevin de Queiroz's "General Lineage Concept of Species".
[src:iucn-red-list/biological-species] An ecological species is a set of organisms adapted to a particular set of resources, called a niche, in the environment.
[src:iucn-red-list/biological-species] According to this concept, populations form the discrete phenetic clusters that we recognise as species because the ecological and evolutionary processes controlling how resources are divided up tend to produce those clusters.
[src:iucn-red-list/biological-species] A genetic species as defined by Robert Baker and Robert Bradley is a set of genetically isolated interbreeding populations.
[src:iucn-red-list/biological-species] This is similar to Mayr's Biological Species Concept, but stresses genetic rather than reproductive isolation.
[src:iucn-red-list/biological-species] In the 21st century, a genetic species could be established by comparing DNA sequences.
[src:iucn-red-list/biological-species] Earlier, other methods were available, such as comparing karyotypes (sets of chromosomes) and allozymes (enzyme variants).
[src:iucn-red-list/biological-species] An evolutionarily significant unit (ESU) or "wildlife species" is a population of organisms considered distinct for purposes of conservation.
[src:iucn-red-list/biological-species] In palaeontology, with only comparative anatomy (morphology) and histology from fossils as evidence, the concept of a chronospecies can be applied.
[src:iucn-red-list/biological-species] During anagenesis (evolution, not necessarily involving branching), some palaeontologists seek to identify a sequence of species, each one derived from the phyletically extinct one before through continuous, slow and more or less uniform change.
[src:iucn-red-list/biological-species] In such a time sequence, some palaeontologists assess how much change is required for a morphologically distinct form to be considered a different species from its ancestors.
[src:iucn-red-list/biological-species] Viruses have enormous populations, are doubtfully living since they consist of little more than a string of DNA or RNA in a protein coat, and mutate rapidly.
[src:iucn-red-list/biological-species] All of these factors make conventional species concepts largely inapplicable.
[src:iucn-red-list/biological-species] A viral quasispecies is a group of genotypes related by similar mutations, competing within a highly mutagenic environment, and hence governed by a mutation–selection balance.
[src:iucn-red-list/biological-species] There is no suggestion that a viral quasispecies resembles a traditional biological species.
[src:iucn-red-list/biological-species] The International Committee on Taxonomy of Viruses has since 1962 developed a universal taxonomic scheme for viruses; this has stabilised viral taxonomy.
[src:iucn-red-list/biological-species] Most modern textbooks make use of Ernst Mayr's 1942 definition, known as the **biological species concept**, as a basis for further discussion on the definition of species.
[src:iucn-red-list/biological-species] It is also called a reproductive or isolation concept.
[src:iucn-red-list/biological-species] It has been argued that this definition is a natural consequence of the effect of sexual reproduction on the dynamics of natural selection.
[src:iucn-red-list/biological-species] Mayr's use of the adjective "potentially" has been a point of debate; some interpretations exclude unusual or artificial matings that occur only in captivity, or that involve animals capable of mating but that do not normally do so in the wild.
[src:iucn-red-list/biological-species] The **renewing species concept** extends Mayr's biological species definition to also include agamous (asexual) organisms.
[src:iucn-red-list/biological-species] It extends the concept of *interbreeding*, the "glue" binding separate individuals into a species, to the concept of *renewal cohesion*, the "glue" that works both for sexual and agamous organisms.
[src:iucn-red-list/biological-species] **Renewal cohesion** is "the restriction of genetic diversity of a group of related individuals as a result of their recent origin from a common ancestor".
[src:iucn-red-list/biological-species] This limitation on genetic diversity results from the effects of genetic drift explained by coalescent theory, which is sufficient to restrict genetic diversity even in the absence of selection.
[src:iucn-red-list/biological-species] Reproductive isolation as "anti-interbreeding" and a prerequisite for speciation, is extended to **renewal isolation**, inclusive of both sexual and agamous organisms.
[src:iucn-red-list/biological-species] Apart from the connection with Mayr's biological species concept, renewing species borrows its mechanism of cohesion from Templeton's "cohesion via genetic drift" (one of **cohesion species** mechanisms described in ).
[src:iucn-red-list/biological-species] It is difficult to define a species in a way that applies to all organisms.
[src:iucn-red-list/biological-species] This debate about species concepts is called the **species problem**.
[src:iucn-red-list/biological-species] are almost identical in appearance but do not interbreed.
[src:iucn-red-list/biological-species] In addition, horizontal gene transfer (HGT) makes it difficult to define a species.
[src:iucn-red-list/biological-species] All species definitions assume that an organism acquires its genes from one or two parents very like the "daughter" organism, but that is not what happens in HGT.
[src:iucn-red-list/biological-species] There is strong evidence of HGT between very dissimilar groups of prokaryotes, and at least occasionally between dissimilar groups of eukaryotes, including some crustaceans and echinoderms.
[src:iucn-red-list/biological-species] The botanist Brent Mishler argued that the species concept is not valid, notably because gene flux decreases gradually rather than in discrete steps, which hampers objective delimitation of species.
[src:iucn-red-list/biological-species] Indeed, complex and unstable patterns of gene flux have been observed in cichlid teleosts of the East African Great Lakes.
[src:iucn-red-list/biological-species] Wilkins argued that "if we were being true to evolution and the consequent phylogenetic approach to taxa, we should replace it with a 'smallest clade' idea" (a phylogenetic species concept).
[src:iucn-red-list/biological-species] Mishler and Wilkins and others concur with this approach, even though this would raise difficulties in biological nomenclature.
[src:iucn-red-list/biological-species] Wilkins cited the ichthyologist Charles Tate Regan's early 20th century remark that "a species is whatever a suitably qualified biologist chooses to call a species".
[src:iucn-red-list/biological-species] Wilkins noted that the philosopher Philip Kitcher called this the "cynical species concept", and arguing that far from being cynical, it usefully leads to an empirical taxonomy for any given group, based on taxonomists' experience.
[src:iucn-red-list/biological-species] Other biologists have gone further and argued that we should abandon species entirely, and refer to the "Least Inclusive Taxonomic Units" (LITUs), a view that would be coherent with current evolutionary theory.
[src:iucn-red-list/biological-species] The species concept is further weakened by the existence of microspecies, groups of organisms, including many plants, with very little genetic variability, usually forming species aggregates.
[src:iucn-red-list/biological-species] Species complexes occur in insects such as *Heliconius* butterflies, vertebrates such as *Hypsiboas* treefrogs, and fungi such as the fly agaric.
[src:iucn-red-list/biological-species] Natural hybridisation presents a challenge to the concept of a reproductively isolated species, as fertile hybrids permit gene flow between two populations.
[src:iucn-red-list/biological-species] For example, the carrion crow *Corvus corone* and the hooded crow *Corvus cornix* appear and are classified as separate species, yet they can hybridise where their geographical ranges overlap.
[src:iucn-red-list/biological-species] Such non-breeding, though genetically connected, "end" populations may co-exist in the same region thus closing the ring.
[src:iucn-red-list/biological-species] Ring species thus present a difficulty for any species concept that relies on reproductive isolation.
[src:iucn-red-list/biological-species] The commonly used names for kinds of organisms are often ambiguous: "cat" could mean the domestic cat, *Felis catus*, or the cat family, Felidae.
[src:iucn-red-list/biological-species] In contrast, the scientific names of species are chosen to be unique and universal (except for some inter-code homonyms); they are in two parts used together: the genus as in *Puma*, and the specific epithet as in *concolor*.
[src:iucn-red-list/biological-species] A species is given a taxonomic name when a type specimen is described formally, in a publication that assigns it a unique scientific name.
[src:iucn-red-list/biological-species] The type material is usually held in a permanent repository, often the research collection of a major museum or university, that allows independent verification and the means to compare specimens.
[src:iucn-red-list/biological-species] Describers of new species are asked to choose names that, in the words of the International Code of Zoological Nomenclature, are "appropriate, compact, euphonious, memorable, and do not cause offence".
[src:iucn-red-list/biological-species] Books and articles sometimes intentionally do not identify species fully, using the abbreviation "**sp.**" in the singular or "**spp.**" in the plural in place of the specific name or epithet (e.g.
[src:iucn-red-list/biological-species] This commonly occurs when authors are confident that some individuals belong to a particular genus but are not sure to which exact species they belong, as is common in paleontology.
[src:iucn-red-list/biological-species] Authors may also use "spp." as a short way of saying that something applies to many species within a genus, but not to all.
[src:iucn-red-list/biological-species] If scientists mean that something applies to all species within a genus, they use the genus name without the specific name or epithet.
[src:iucn-red-list/biological-species] The names of genera and species are usually printed in italics.
[src:iucn-red-list/biological-species] However, abbreviations such as "sp." should not be italicised.
[src:iucn-red-list/biological-species] When a species' identity is not clear, a specialist may use "cf." before the epithet to indicate that confirmation is required.
[src:iucn-red-list/biological-species] The abbreviations "nr." (near) or "aff." (affine) may be used when the identity is unclear but when the species appears to be similar to the species mentioned after.
[src:iucn-red-list/biological-species] The naming of a particular species, including which genus (and higher taxa) it is placed in, is a *hypothesis* about the evolutionary relationships and distinguishability of that group of organisms.
[src:iucn-red-list/biological-species] As further information comes to hand, the hypothesis may be corroborated or refuted.
[src:iucn-red-list/biological-species] Sometimes, especially in the past when communication was more difficult, taxonomists working in isolation have given two distinct names to individual organisms later identified as the same species.
[src:iucn-red-list/biological-species] When two species names are discovered to apply to the same species, the older species name is given priority and usually retained, and the newer name considered as a junior synonym, a process called *synonymy*.
[src:iucn-red-list/biological-species] Dividing a taxon into multiple, often new, taxa is called *splitting*.
[src:iucn-red-list/biological-species] Taxonomists are often referred to as "lumpers" or "splitters" by their colleagues, depending on their personal approach to recognising differences or commonalities between organisms.
[src:iucn-red-list/biological-species] The nomenclatural codes that guide the naming of species, including the ICZN for animals and the ICN for plants, do not make rules for defining the boundaries of the species.
[src:iucn-red-list/biological-species] Research can change the boundaries, also known as circumscription, based on new evidence.
[src:iucn-red-list/biological-species] Other abbreviations such as "auct." ("author"), and qualifiers such as "non" ("not") may be used to further clarify the sense in which the specified authors delineated or described the species.
[src:iucn-red-list/biological-species] Species are subject to change, whether by evolving into new species, exchanging genes with other species, merging with other species or by becoming extinct.
[src:iucn-red-list/biological-species] The evolutionary process by which biological populations of sexually-reproducing organisms evolve to become distinct or reproductively isolated as species is called speciation.
[src:iucn-red-list/biological-species] Charles Darwin was the first to describe the role of natural selection in speciation in his 1859 book *The Origin of Species*.
[src:iucn-red-list/biological-species] Speciation depends on a measure of reproductive isolation, a reduced gene flow.
[src:iucn-red-list/biological-species] This occurs most easily in allopatric speciation, where populations are separated geographically and can diverge gradually as mutations accumulate.
[src:iucn-red-list/biological-species] Reproductive isolation is threatened by hybridisation, but this can be selected against once a pair of populations have incompatible alleles of the same gene, as described in the Bateson–Dobzhansky–Muller model.
[src:iucn-red-list/biological-species] A different mechanism, phyletic speciation, involves one lineage gradually changing over time into a new and distinct form (a chronospecies), without increasing the number of resultant species.
[src:iucn-red-list/biological-species] Horizontal gene transfer between organisms of different species, either through hybridisation, antigenic shift, or reassortment, is sometimes an important source of genetic variation.
[src:iucn-red-list/biological-species] Viruses can transfer genes between species.
[src:iucn-red-list/biological-species] Bacteria can exchange plasmids with bacteria of other species, including some apparently distantly related ones in different phylogenetic domains, making analysis of their relationships difficult, and weakening the concept of a bacterial species.
[src:iucn-red-list/biological-species] Louis-Marie Bobay and Howard Ochman suggest, based on analysis of the genomes of many types of bacteria, that they can often be grouped "into communities that regularly swap genes", in much the same way that plants and animals can be grouped into reproductively isolated breeding populations.
[src:iucn-red-list/biological-species] Bacteria may thus form species, analogous to Mayr's biological species concept, consisting of asexually reproducing populations that exchange genes by homologous recombination.
[src:iucn-red-list/biological-species] A species is extinct when the last individual of that species dies, but it may be functionally extinct well before that moment.
[src:iucn-red-list/biological-species] It is estimated that over 99 percent of all species that ever lived on Earth, some five billion species, are now extinct.
[src:iucn-red-list/biological-species] Some of these were in mass extinctions such as those at the ends of the Ordovician, Devonian, Permian, Triassic and Cretaceous periods.
[src:iucn-red-list/biological-species] Mass extinctions had a variety of causes including volcanic activity, climate change, and changes in oceanic and atmospheric chemistry, and they in turn had major effects on Earth's ecology, atmosphere, land surface and waters.
[src:iucn-red-list/biological-species] Another form of extinction is through the assimilation of one species by another through hybridization.
[src:iucn-red-list/biological-species] The resulting single species has been termed as a "compilospecies".
[src:iucn-red-list/biological-species] Biologists and conservationists need to categorise and identify organisms in the course of their work.
[src:iucn-red-list/biological-species] Difficulty assigning organisms reliably to a species constitutes a threat to the validity of research results, for example making measurements of how abundant a species is in an ecosystem moot.
[src:iucn-red-list/biological-species] Some observers claim that there is an inherent conflict between the desire to understand the processes of speciation and the need to identify and to categorise.
[src:iucn-red-list/biological-species] Conservation laws in many countries make special provisions to prevent species from going extinct.
[src:iucn-red-list/biological-species] Hybridization zones between two species, one that is protected and one that is not, have sometimes led to conflicts between lawmakers, land owners and conservationists.
[src:iucn-red-list/biological-species] One of the classic cases in North America is that of the protected northern spotted owl which hybridises with the unprotected California spotted owl and the barred owl; this has led to legal debates.
[src:iucn-red-list/biological-species] It has been argued, that since species are not comparable, simply counting them is not a valid measure of biodiversity; alternative measures of phylogenetic biodiversity have been proposed.
[src:iucn-red-list/biological-species] In his biology, Aristotle used the term γένος (génos) to mean a kind, such as a bird or fish, and εἶδος (eidos) to mean a specific form within a kind, such as (within the birds) the crane, eagle, crow, or sparrow.
[src:iucn-red-list/biological-species] These terms were translated into Latin as "genus" and "species", though they do not correspond to the Linnean terms thus named; today the birds are a class, the cranes are a family, and the crows a genus.
[src:iucn-red-list/biological-species] A kind was distinguished by its attributes; for instance, a bird has feathers, a beak, wings, a hard-shelled egg, and warm blood.
[src:iucn-red-list/biological-species] A form was distinguished by being shared by all its members, the young inheriting any variations they might have from their parents.
[src:iucn-red-list/biological-species] Aristotle believed all kinds and forms to be distinct and unchanging.
[src:iucn-red-list/biological-species] More importantly, in Aristotle's works, the terms γένος (génos) and εἶδος (eidos) are relative; a taxon that is considered an eidos in a given context can be considered a génos in another, and be further subdivided into eide (plural of eidos).
[src:iucn-red-list/biological-species] His approach remained influential until the Renaissance, and still, to a lower extent, today.
[src:iucn-red-list/biological-species] When observers in the Early Modern period began to develop systems of organization for living things, they placed each kind of animal or plant into a context.
[src:iucn-red-list/biological-species] Many of these early delineation schemes would now be considered whimsical: schemes included consanguinity based on colour (all plants with yellow flowers) or behaviour (snakes, scorpions and certain biting ants).
[src:iucn-red-list/biological-species] In the 18th century, the Swedish scientist Carl Linnaeus classified organisms according to shared physical characteristics, and not simply based upon differences.
[src:iucn-red-list/biological-species] Like many contemporary systematists, he established the idea of a taxonomic hierarchy of classification based upon observable characteristics and intended to reflect natural relationships.
[src:iucn-red-list/biological-species] At the time, however, it was still widely believed that there was no organic connection between species (except, possibly, between those of a given genus), no matter how similar they appeared.
[src:iucn-red-list/biological-species] This view was influenced by European scholarly and religious education, which held that the taxa had been created by God, forming an Aristotelian hierarchy, the *scala naturae* or great chain of being.
[src:iucn-red-list/biological-species] However, whether or not it was supposed to be fixed, the *scala* (a ladder) inherently implied the possibility of climbing.
[src:iucn-red-list/biological-species] In viewing evidence of hybridisation, Linnaeus recognised that species were not fixed and could change; he did not consider that new species could emerge and maintained a view of divinely fixed species that may alter through processes of hybridisation or acclimatisation.
[src:iucn-red-list/biological-species] By the 19th century, naturalists understood that species could change form over time, and that the history of the planet provided enough time for major changes.
[src:iucn-red-list/biological-species] Jean-Baptiste Lamarck, in his 1809 *Zoological Philosophy*, described the transmutation of species, proposing that a species could change over time, in a radical departure from Aristotelian thinking.
[src:iucn-red-list/biological-species] In 1858, Charles Darwin and Alfred Russel Wallace provided a compelling account of evolution and the formation of new species.
[src:iucn-red-list/biological-species] Darwin argued that it was populations that evolved, not individuals, by natural selection from naturally occurring variation among individuals.
[src:iucn-red-list/biological-species] This required a new definition of species.
[src:iucn-red-list/bird-p01] Birds evolved from earlier theropods, and thus constitute the only known living dinosaurs.
[src:iucn-red-list/bird-p01] Whilst traditional Linnaean taxonomy placed birds in their own class (owing to their unique morphology and being the only group of animals other than mammals where all its species are warm-blooded), birds are considered reptiles in the modern cladistic sense of the term.
[src:iucn-red-list/bird-p01] Their closest living relatives are the crocodilians, both forming a clade known as archosaurs.
[src:iucn-red-list/bird-p01] Birds are descendants of the primitive avialans (whose members include *Archaeopteryx*) which first appeared during the Late Jurassic.
[src:iucn-red-list/bird-p01] Many social species preserve knowledge across generations (culture).
[src:iucn-red-list/bird-p01] Birds are social, communicating with visual signals, calls, and songs, and participating in such behaviour as cooperative breeding and hunting, flocking, and mobbing of predators.
[src:iucn-red-list/bird-p01] The vast majority of bird species are socially (but not necessarily sexually) monogamous, usually for one breeding season at a time, sometimes for years, and rarely for life.
[src:iucn-red-list/bird-p01] Other species have breeding systems that are polygynous (one male with many females) or, rarely, polyandrous (one female with many males).
[src:iucn-red-list/bird-p01] Birds produce offspring by laying eggs which are fertilised through sexual reproduction.
[src:iucn-red-list/bird-p01] They are usually laid in a nest and incubated by the parents.
[src:iucn-red-list/bird-p01] Most birds have an extended period of parental care after hatching.
[src:iucn-red-list/bird-p01] Many species of birds are economically important as food for human consumption and raw material in manufacturing, with domesticated and undomesticated birds being important sources of eggs, meat, and feathers.
[src:iucn-red-list/bird-p01] Songbirds, parrots, and other species are popular as pets.
[src:iucn-red-list/bird-p01] Guano (bird excrement) is harvested for use as a fertiliser.
[src:iucn-red-list/bird-p01] About 120 to 130 species have become extinct due to human activity since the 17th century, and hundreds more before then.
[src:iucn-red-list/bird-p01] Human activity threatens about 1,200 bird species with extinction, though efforts are underway to protect them.
[src:iucn-red-list/bird-p01] Recreational birdwatching is an important part of the ecotourism industry.
[src:iucn-red-list/bird-p01] The first classification of birds was developed by Francis Willughby and John Ray in their 1676 volume *Ornithologiae*.
[src:iucn-red-list/bird-p01] Carl Linnaeus modified that work in 1758 to devise the taxonomic classification system currently in use.
[src:iucn-red-list/bird-p01] Birds are usually categorised as a biological class in traditional evolutionary taxonomy.
[src:iucn-red-list/bird-p01] Modern phylogenetic taxonomy places Aves in the clade Theropoda, sometimes with a Linnean rank lower than class, such as subclass or infraclass.
[src:iucn-red-list/bird-p01] Aves and a sister group, the order Crocodilia, contain the only living representatives of the reptile clade Archosauria.
[src:iucn-red-list/bird-p01] During the late 1990s, Aves was most commonly defined phylogenetically as all descendants of the most recent common ancestor of modern birds and *Archaeopteryx lithographica*.
[src:iucn-red-list/bird-p01] However, an earlier definition proposed by Jacques Gauthier gained wide currency in the 21st century, and is used by many scientists including adherents to the *PhyloCode*.
[src:iucn-red-list/bird-p01] Gauthier defined Aves to include only the crown group of the set of modern birds.
[src:iucn-red-list/bird-p01] This was done by excluding most groups known only from fossils, and assigning them, instead, to the broader group Avialae, on the principle that a clade based on extant species should be limited to those extant species and their closest extinct relatives.
[src:iucn-red-list/bird-p01] Gauthier and de Queiroz identified four different definitions for the same biological name "Aves", which is a problem.
[src:iucn-red-list/bird-p01] The authors proposed to reserve the term Aves only for the crown group consisting of the last common ancestor of all living birds and all of its descendants, which corresponds to meaning number 4 below.
[src:iucn-red-list/bird-p01] They assigned other names to the other groups.
[src:iucn-red-list/bird-p01] Under the fourth definition *Archaeopteryx*, traditionally considered one of the earliest members of Aves, is removed from this group, becoming a non-avian dinosaur instead.
[src:iucn-red-list/bird-p01] These proposals have been adopted by many researchers in the field of palaeontology and bird evolution, though the exact definitions applied have been inconsistent.
[src:iucn-red-list/bird-p01] Avialae, initially proposed to replace the traditional fossil content of Aves, is often used synonymously with the vernacular term "bird" by these researchers.
[src:iucn-red-list/bird-p01] Most researchers define Avialae as branch-based clade, though definitions vary.
[src:iucn-red-list/bird-p01] Many authors have used a definition similar to "all theropods closer to birds than to *Deinonychus*", with *Troodon* being sometimes added as a second external specifier in case it is closer to birds than to *Deinonychus*.
[src:iucn-red-list/bird-p01] Avialae is also occasionally defined as an apomorphy-based clade (that is, one based on physical characteristics).
[src:iucn-red-list/bird-p01] Jacques Gauthier, who named Avialae in 1986, re-defined it in 2001 as all dinosaurs that possessed feathered wings used in flapping flight, and the birds that descended from them.
[src:iucn-red-list/bird-p01] Despite being currently one of the most widely used, the crown-group definition of Aves has been criticised by some researchers.
[src:iucn-red-list/bird-p01] Their alternative definition is synonymous to Avifilopluma.
[src:iucn-red-list/bird-p01] Based on fossil and biological evidence, most scientists accept that birds are a specialised subgroup of theropod dinosaurs and, more specifically, members of Maniraptora, a group of theropods which includes dromaeosaurids and oviraptorosaurs, among others.
[src:iucn-red-list/bird-p01] As scientists have discovered more theropods closely related to birds, the previously clear distinction between non-birds and birds has become blurred.
[src:iucn-red-list/bird-p01] By the 2000s, discoveries in the Liaoning Province of northeast China, which demonstrated many small theropod feathered dinosaurs, contributed to this ambiguity.
[src:iucn-red-list/bird-p01] The consensus view in contemporary palaeontology is that the flying theropods, or avialans, are the closest relatives of the deinonychosaurs, which include dromaeosaurids and troodontids.
[src:iucn-red-list/bird-p01] Together, these form a group called Paraves.
[src:iucn-red-list/bird-p01] Some basal members of Deinonychosauria, such as *Microraptor*, have features which may have enabled them to glide or fly.
[src:iucn-red-list/bird-p01] The most basal deinonychosaurs were very small.
[src:iucn-red-list/bird-p01] This evidence raises the possibility that the ancestor of all paravians may have been arboreal, have been able to glide, or both.
[src:iucn-red-list/bird-p01] Unlike *Archaeopteryx* and the non-avialan feathered dinosaurs, who primarily ate meat, studies suggest that the first avialans were omnivores.
[src:iucn-red-list/bird-p01] The Late Jurassic *Archaeopteryx* is well known as one of the first transitional fossils to be found, and it provided support for the theory of evolution in the late 19th century.
[src:iucn-red-list/bird-p01] *Archaeopteryx* was the first fossil to display both clearly traditional reptilian characteristics—teeth, clawed fingers, and a long, lizard-like tail—as well as wings with flight feathers similar to those of modern birds.
[src:iucn-red-list/bird-p01] It is not considered a direct ancestor of birds, though it is possibly closely related to the true ancestor.
[src:iucn-red-list/bird-p01] Over 40% of key traits found in modern birds evolved during the 60 million year transition from the earliest bird-line archosaurs to the first maniraptoromorphs, i.e. the first dinosaurs closer to living birds than to *Tyrannosaurus rex*.
[src:iucn-red-list/bird-p01] The loss of osteoderms otherwise common in archosaurs and acquisition of primitive feathers might have occurred early during this phase.
[src:iucn-red-list/bird-p01] After the appearance of Maniraptoromorpha, the next 40 million years marked a continuous reduction of body size and the accumulation of neotenic (juvenile-like) characteristics.
[src:iucn-red-list/bird-p01] Hypercarnivory became increasingly less common while braincases enlarged and forelimbs became longer.
[src:iucn-red-list/bird-p01] The integument evolved into complex, pennaceous feathers.
[src:iucn-red-list/bird-p01] The oldest known paravian (and probably the earliest avialan) fossils come from the Tiaojishan Formation of China, which has been dated to the late Jurassic period (Oxfordian stage), about 160 million years ago.
[src:iucn-red-list/bird-p01] The avialan species from this time period include *Anchiornis huxleyi*, *Xiaotingia zhengi*, and *Aurornis xui*.
[src:iucn-red-list/bird-p01] The well-known probable early avialan, *Archaeopteryx*, dates from slightly later Jurassic rocks (about 155 million years old) from Germany.
[src:iucn-red-list/bird-p01] Many of these early avialans shared unusual anatomical features that may be ancestral to modern birds but were later lost during bird evolution.
[src:iucn-red-list/bird-p01] These features include enlarged claws on the second toe which may have been held clear of the ground in life, and long feathers or "hind wings" covering the hind limbs and feet, which may have been used in aerial maneuvering.
[src:iucn-red-list/bird-p01] Avialans diversified into a wide variety of forms during the Cretaceous period.
[src:iucn-red-list/bird-p01] Many groups retained primitive characteristics, such as clawed wings and teeth, though the latter were lost independently in a number of avialan groups, including modern birds (Aves).
[src:iucn-red-list/bird-p01] Increasingly stiff tails (especially the outermost half) can be seen in the evolution of maniraptoromorphs, and this process culminated in the appearance of the pygostyle, an ossification of fused tail vertebrae.
[src:iucn-red-list/bird-p01] In the late Cretaceous, about 100 million years ago, the ancestors of all modern birds evolved a more open pelvis, allowing them to lay larger eggs compared to body size.
[src:iucn-red-list/bird-p01] Around 95 million years ago, they evolved a better sense of smell.
[src:iucn-red-list/bird-p01] A third stage of bird evolution starting with Ornithothoraces (the "bird-chested" avialans) can be associated with the refining of aerodynamics and flight capabilities, and the loss or co-ossification of several skeletal features.
[src:iucn-red-list/bird-p01] Particularly significant are the development of an enlarged, keeled sternum and the alula, and the loss of grasping hands.
[src:iucn-red-list/bird-p01] The first large, diverse lineage of short-tailed avialans to evolve were the Enantiornithes, or "opposite birds", so named because the construction of their shoulder bones was in reverse to that of modern birds.
[src:iucn-red-list/bird-p01] Enantiornithes occupied a wide array of ecological niches, from sand-probing shorebirds and fish-eaters to tree-dwelling forms and seed-eaters.
[src:iucn-red-list/bird-p01] While they were the dominant group of avialans during the Cretaceous period, Enantiornithes became extinct along with many other dinosaur groups at the end of the Mesozoic era.
[src:iucn-red-list/bird-p01] Many species of the second major avialan lineage to diversify, the Euornithes (meaning "true birds", because they include the ancestors of modern birds), were semi-aquatic and specialised in eating fish and other small aquatic organisms.
[src:iucn-red-list/bird-p01] Unlike the Enantiornithes, which dominated land-based and arboreal habitats, most early euornithians lacked perching adaptations and likely included shorebird-like species, waders, and swimming and diving species.
[src:iucn-red-list/bird-p01] The latter included the superficially gull-like *Ichthyornis* and the Hesperornithiformes, which became so well adapted to hunting fish in marine environments that they lost the ability to fly and became primarily aquatic.
[src:iucn-red-list/bird-p01] The early euornithians also saw the development of many traits associated with modern birds, like strongly keeled breastbones, toothless, beaked portions of their jaws (though most non-avian euornithians retained teeth in other parts of the jaws).
[src:iucn-red-list/bird-p01] Euornithes also included the first avialans to develop true pygostyle and a fully mobile fan of tail feathers, which may have replaced the "hind wing" as the primary mode of aerial maneuverability and braking in flight.
[src:iucn-red-list/bird-p01] A study on mosaic evolution in the avian skull found that the last common ancestor of all Neornithes might have had a beak similar to that of the modern hook-billed vanga and a skull similar to that of the Eurasian golden oriole.
[src:iucn-red-list/bird-p01] As both species are small aerial and canopy foraging omnivores, a similar ecological niche was inferred for this hypothetical ancestor.
[src:iucn-red-list/bird-p01] Most studies agree on a Cretaceous age for the most recent common ancestor of modern birds but estimates range from the Early Cretaceous to the latest Cretaceous.
[src:iucn-red-list/bird-p01] Similarly, there is no agreement on whether most of the early diversification of modern birds occurred in the Cretaceous and associated with breakup of the supercontinent Gondwana or occurred later and potentially as a consequence of the Cretaceous–Palaeogene extinction event.
[src:iucn-red-list/bird-p01] This disagreement is in part caused by a divergence in the evidence; most molecular dating studies suggests a Cretaceous evolutionary radiation, while fossil evidence points to a Cenozoic radiation (the so-called 'rocks' versus 'clocks' controversy).
[src:iucn-red-list/bird-p01] The discovery in 2005 of *Vegavis* from the Maastrichtian, the last stage of the Late Cretaceous, proved that the diversification of modern birds started before the Cenozoic era.
[src:iucn-red-list/bird-p01] The affinities of an earlier fossil, the possible galliform *Austinornis lentus*, dated to about 85 million years ago, are still too controversial to provide a fossil evidence of modern bird diversification.
[src:iucn-red-list/bird-p01] In 2020, *Asteriornis* from the Maastrichtian was described, it appears to be a close relative of Galloanserae, the earliest diverging lineage within Neognathae.
[src:iucn-red-list/bird-p01] Attempts to reconcile molecular and fossil evidence using genomic-scale DNA data and comprehensive fossil information have not resolved the controversy.
[src:iucn-red-list/bird-p01] However, a 2015 estimate that used a new method for calibrating molecular clocks confirmed that while modern birds originated early in the Late Cretaceous, likely in Western Gondwana, a pulse of diversification in all major groups occurred around the Cretaceous–Palaeogene extinction event.
[src:iucn-red-list/bird-p01] Modern birds would have expanded from West Gondwana through two routes.
[src:iucn-red-list/bird-p01] One route was an Antarctic interchange in the Paleogene.
[src:iucn-red-list/bird-p01] The other route was probably via Paleocene land bridges between South America and North America, which allowed for the rapid expansion and diversification of Neornithes into the Holarctic and Paleotropics.
[src:iucn-red-list/bird-p01] On the other hand, the occurrence of *Asteriornis* in the Northern Hemisphere suggest that Neornithes dispersed out of East Gondwana before the Paleocene.
[src:iucn-red-list/bird-p01] All modern birds lie within the crown group Aves (alternately Neornithes), which has two subdivisions: the Palaeognathae, which includes the flightless ratites (such as the ostriches) and the weak-flying tinamous, and the extremely diverse Neognathae, containing all other birds.
[src:iucn-red-list/bird-p01] These two subdivisions have variously been given the rank of superorder, cohort, or infraclass.
[src:iucn-red-list/bird-p01] The number of known living bird species is around 11,000 although sources may differ in their precise numbers.
[src:iucn-red-list/bird-p01] Cladogram of modern bird relationships based on Stiller *et al* (2024)., showing the 44 orders recognised by the IOC.
[src:iucn-red-list/bird-p01] The classification of birds is a contentious issue.
[src:iucn-red-list/bird-p01] Sibley and Ahlquist's *Phylogeny and Classification of Birds* (1990) is a landmark work on the subject.
[src:iucn-red-list/bird-p01] Most evidence seems to suggest the assignment of orders is accurate, but scientists disagree about the relationships among the orders themselves; evidence from modern bird anatomy, fossils and DNA have all been brought to bear on the problem, but no strong consensus has emerged.
[src:iucn-red-list/bird-p01] Fossil and molecular evidence from the 2010s is providing an increasingly clear picture of the evolution of modern bird orders.
[src:iucn-red-list/bird-p01] In 2010, the genome had been sequenced for only two birds, the chicken and the zebra finch.
[src:iucn-red-list/bird-p01] As of 2022, the genomes of 542 species of birds had been completed.
[src:iucn-red-list/bird-p01] At least one genome has been sequenced from every order.
[src:iucn-red-list/bird-p01] These include at least one species in about 90% of extant avian families (218 out of 236 families recognised by the *Howard and Moore Checklist*).
[src:iucn-red-list/bird-p01] Being able to sequence and compare whole genomes gives researchers many types of information, about genes, the DNA that regulates the genes, and their evolutionary history.
[src:iucn-red-list/bird-p01] This has led to reconsideration of some of the classifications that were based solely on the identification of protein-coding genes.
[src:iucn-red-list/bird-p01] Waterbirds such as pelicans and flamingos, for example, may have in common specific adaptations suited to their environment that were developed independently.
[src:iucn-red-list/bird-p01] Birds live and breed in most terrestrial habitats and on all seven continents, reaching their southern extreme in the snow petrel's breeding colonies up to 440 kilometres (270 mi) inland in Antarctica.
[src:iucn-red-list/bird-p01] The highest bird diversity occurs in tropical regions.
[src:iucn-red-list/bird-p01] It was earlier thought that this high diversity was the result of higher speciation rates in the tropics; however studies from the 2000s found higher speciation rates in the high latitudes that were offset by greater extinction rates than in the tropics.
[src:iucn-red-list/bird-p01] Many species migrate annually over great distances and across oceans; several families of birds have adapted to life both on the world's oceans and in them, and some seabird species come ashore only to breed, while some penguins have been recorded diving up to 300 metres (980 ft) deep.
[src:iucn-red-list/bird-p01] Many bird species have established breeding populations in areas to which they have been introduced by humans.
[src:iucn-red-list/bird-p01] Some of these introductions have been deliberate; the ring-necked pheasant, for example, has been introduced around the world as a game bird.
[src:iucn-red-list/bird-p01] Others have been accidental, such as the establishment of wild monk parakeets in several North American cities after their escape from captivity.
[src:iucn-red-list/bird-p01] Some species, including cattle egret, yellow-headed caracara and galah, have spread naturally far beyond their original ranges as agricultural expansion created alternative habitats although modern practices of intensive agriculture have negatively impacted farmland bird populations.
[src:iucn-red-list/bird-p01] Compared with other vertebrates, birds have a body plan that shows many unusual adaptations, mostly to facilitate flight.
[src:iucn-red-list/bird-p01] The skeleton consists of very lightweight bones.
[src:iucn-red-list/bird-p01] They have large air-filled cavities (called pneumatic cavities) which connect with the respiratory system.
[src:iucn-red-list/bird-p01] The skull bones in adults are fused and do not show cranial sutures.
[src:iucn-red-list/bird-p01] The orbital cavities that house the eyeballs are large and separated from each other by a bony septum (partition).
[src:iucn-red-list/bird-p01] The spine has cervical, thoracic, lumbar and caudal regions with the number of cervical (neck) vertebrae highly variable and especially flexible, but movement is reduced in the anterior thoracic vertebrae and absent in the later vertebrae.
[src:iucn-red-list/bird-p01] The last few are fused with the pelvis to form the synsacrum.
[src:iucn-red-list/bird-p01] The ribs are flattened and the sternum is keeled for the attachment of flight muscles except in the flightless bird orders.
[src:iucn-red-list/bird-p01] The wings are more or less developed depending on the species; the only known groups that lost their wings are the extinct moa and elephant birds.
[src:iucn-red-list/bird-p01] Like reptiles, birds are primarily uricotelic; that is, their kidneys extract nitrogenous waste from their bloodstream and excrete it as uric acid, instead of urea or ammonia, through the ureters into the intestine.
[src:iucn-red-list/bird-p01] Birds do not have a urinary bladder or external urethral opening.
[src:iucn-red-list/bird-p01] With the exception of the ostrich, uric acid is excreted along with faeces as a semisolid waste.
[src:iucn-red-list/bird-p01] However, birds such as hummingbirds can be facultatively ammonotelic, excreting most of the nitrogenous wastes as ammonia.
[src:iucn-red-list/bird-p01] They also excrete creatine, rather than creatinine like mammals.
[src:iucn-red-list/bird-p01] This material, as well as the output of the intestines, emerges from the bird's cloaca.
[src:iucn-red-list/bird-p01] The cloaca is a multi-purpose opening: waste is expelled through it, most birds mate by joining cloaca, and females lay eggs from it.
[src:iucn-red-list/bird-p01] In addition, many species of birds regurgitate pellets.
[src:iucn-red-list/bird-p01] It is a common but not universal feature of altricial passerine nestlings (born helpless, under constant parental care) that instead of excreting directly into the nest, they produce a fecal sac.
[src:iucn-red-list/bird-p01] This is a mucus-covered pouch that allows parents to either dispose of the waste outside the nest or to recycle the waste through their own digestive system.
[src:iucn-red-list/bird-p01] Most male birds do not have intromittent penises.
[src:iucn-red-list/bird-p01] Males within Palaeognathae (with the exception of the kiwis), the Anseriformes (with the exception of screamers), and in rudimentary forms in Galliformes (but fully developed in Cracidae) possess a penis, which is never present in Neoaves.
[src:iucn-red-list/bird-p01] Its length is thought to be related to sperm competition and it fills with lymphatic fluid instead of blood when erect.
[src:iucn-red-list/bird-p01] When not copulating, it is hidden within the proctodeum compartment within the cloaca, just inside the vent.
[src:iucn-red-list/bird-p01] Female birds have sperm storage tubules that allow sperm to remain viable long after copulation, a hundred days in some species.
[src:iucn-red-list/bird-p01] Sperm from multiple males may compete through this mechanism.
[src:iucn-red-list/bird-p01] Most female birds have a single ovary and a single oviduct, both on the left side, but there are exceptions: species in at least 16 different orders of birds have two ovaries.
[src:iucn-red-list/bird-p01] Even these species, however, tend to have a single oviduct.
